<HEADLINE> Israel's 1997 Financial Deficit Drops Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Israel's 1997 financial
deficit was only half of that for 1996, standing at 8.124 billion
shekels (about 2.32 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Last year's financial deficit represents 2.4 percent of the
gross domestic product (GDP), 2.5 percentage points lower than
that of 1996, according to The Jerusalem Post today.
</P>
<P>
It is also lower than the budgeted deficit of last year, which
was originally set to 9.744 billion shekels (2.78 billion
dollars), or 2.8 percent of the GDP.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted Israeli Account General Shai Talmon as
saying that the main reason for the decrease was the privatizing
process of the state-owned companies, which has been accelerated
by the Likud government since it came to power one year and a half
ago.
</P>
<P>
He said that 8.5 billion shekels (2.43 billion dollars) was
earned from privatization in 1997, particularly the sale of
government interests in Bank Hapoalim, the largest bank of Israel.
</P>
<P>
"During the year of 1997, the government did not fund its
deficits by taking loans," he said.
</P>
<P>
The government has been carrying out a large-scale economic
reform to reduce the financial deficit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
