<DOCNO> XIE19980109.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Producer Prices Record sharpest Decline in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. producers prices
paid by wholesalers fell in December for the ninth month this
year, bringing the price decline for 1997 to 1.2 percent, the
largest deflation since 1986, the Labor Department said today.
</P>
<P>
In contrast to the 2.3 percent drop mainly because of
oil prices in 1986, declines last year were much more broad-based.
They ranged from gasoline to eggs to cars to computers, the
department noted.
</P>
<P>
In December, the department's Producer Price Index (PPI), which
measures prices paid to producers such as factories and
food-processing plants, fell 0.2 percent, the same as in November.
</P>
<P>
For the whole year, energy costs fell 6.4 percent after
shooting up 11.7 percent in 1996. Food prices fell 1 percent after
advancing 3.4 percent the year before.
</P>
<P>
The so-called core rate of producer price inflation, finished
goods excluding the volatile food and energy components, moved a
0.1 percent higher for all of 1997 after rising 0.6 percent in
1996. It was the smallest rise on record since the department
began tracking the core rate in 1973.
</P>
<P>
The consumer prices still are increasing at about a 1.8 percent
rate in 1997, largely due to service prices. It was influenced by
tight U.S. labor markets.
</P>
<P>
Gasoline prices at year-end were 14.9 percent lower than 12
months earlier. Fuel oil fell 21.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Egg costs were down 15.6 percent; pork, 13.9 percent; chickens,
10.1 percent; fresh fruit, 9.6 percent, and processed fruit and
vegetables, 2.7 percent. Coffee, though, soared 18.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Household appliance prices fell 2.6 percent; cars, 1.7 percent
and light trucks, 3.1 percent. All were influenced by competition
with imports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
