<HEADLINE> Zambia Needs an Aggressive Foreign Policy, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Zambian Foreign Minister Keli
Walubita said today that Zambia needs to develop an aggressive
and dynamic foreign policy if it has to beat competition for
resources, investment, technology and markets in the world,
Zambia News Agency ZANA reported.
</P>
<P>
Opening a workshop on performance review for the Ministry of
Foreign Affairs in Siavonga, a town on the Zambia-Zimbabwe
border, Walubita said that countries are becoming closely
interlinked through advanced means of communication, technology,
hence there is need for an aggressive foreign policy to enhance
investment flow into Zambia.
</P>
<P>
"Expenditure has shown that there is a strong link between a
dynamic and aggressive foreign policy and trade and investment
flow into a country, hence effective strategies should be
obvious," said the foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
He called on the participants to the workshop to devise
strategies that would take the country to the year 2001 and
beyond.
</P>
<P>
Walubita also stressed the need to strengthen relations with
the Democratic Republic of Congo, with which Zambia shares the
longest common border.
</P>
<P>
There is still potential for the two neighbours to increase
cooperation in mining, power and transport, communication and
other areas for the mutual benefit and development of the people
of the two countries, said Walubita.
</P>
<P>
The workshop is aimed at, among other issues, enabling the
Ministry of Foreign Affairs to respond to some negative
sentiments about the country abroad, according to ZANA. 
</P>
</TEXT>
