<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Clamps Down On Smuggling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 8 (Xinhua) -- China has confiscated
approximately 10,400 guns, more than 4.62 million grams of heroin
and some 2.12 million grams of opium in border regions over the
past five years.
</P>
<P>
The majority of smuggled items crossed the border in
southwest China where crimes gun-running and drugs smuggling were
rampant in 1993, according to Li Jizhou, vice-minister of public
security.
</P>
<P>
Chinese public security bureaus have arrested 2,196
"snakeheads", or the men who organized smuggling activities, and
some 52,760 so-called "mules"
</P>
<P>
Security departments have successfully concluded the biggest
maritime smuggling case in the country's 48-year history with the
confiscations of goods valued at 200 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, security departments also concluded three currency
counterfeiting operations and confiscated fake currency valued at
140 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
Some 4,000 cases handled over the past five years have involved
items valued at more than 4.38 billion yuan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
