<HEADLINE> Algeria has Accepted EU Mission, Kinkel Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, January 8 (Xinhua) -- German Foreign Minister Klaus
Kinkel Thursday said that the Algerian government has approved the
visit of a European Union mission which would seek to offer help
to stem a recent surge of massacres in the northwest African
country.
</P>
<P>
Kinkel said he had received the news on Wednesday evening from
his British counterpart Robin Cook, who now holds the rotating
presidency of the EU.
</P>
<P>
The EU would now send high-ranking representatives from
Britain, Luxembourg and Austria to Algeria as soon as possible,
Kinkel said, adding that the EU envoys would hold talks with the
Algerian government on ways to combat terrorism and to offer
humanitarian help to the victims.
</P>
<P>
Sending an EU mission to Algeria was initiated by Kinkel over
the weekend after the reported massacre of over 400 Algerian
civilians early last week. The Algerian government previously had
rejected all outside interference.
</P>
<P>
Cook told Kinkel that Algeria had also approved a visit by a
United Nations observer mission. 
</P>
</TEXT>
