<DOCNO> XIE19980109.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNESCO to Support Three Gorges Underwater Museum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Education,
Science and Culture Organization (UNESCO) has financed the
publication of an illustrated book covering the planning of an
underwater museum to protect ancient carvings on an 1.6-km ridge
in the Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
In the forward for the book, UNESCO Director General Federico
Mayor wrote: "UNESCO is delighted to join the Chinese Government
in an effort to preserve the White Crane Ridge."
</P>
<P>
White Crane Ridge, the rock formation which features carving of
18 fish, surfaced annually in the Yangtze River between spring
and summer when the water level is comparatively low.
</P>
<P>
Over the past millennia, local residents have traveled to the
ridge which also features some 30,000 inscriptions carved by poets
and local officials over the past 1,200 years.
</P>
<P>
Archeologists noted that inscriptions date to an earlier period
and are greater in number than the famous low-water carvings along
the Nile in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
However, the ridge will be permanently submerged upon completion
of the Three Gorges Project, China's largest water conservancy
project,
</P>
<P>
In hopes of preserving the carvings and keeping them in good
shape, Chinese experts have carried out geological studies and
underwater archeological research around the ridge, and have in
turn completed a detailed design for a museum.
</P>
<P>
The design calls for an underwater double-shelled structure
covering the inscriptions found on some 220 meters of the ridge.
</P>
<P>
So visitors will still be able to view the inscriptions via a
130 meter underwater passageway and exhibition hall.
</P>
<P>
The project will be completed over the next 10 years at a cost
of approximately 100 million yuan (12 million US dollars).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980109.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seminar on Yangtze River Valley Environment Held in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, January 8 (Xinhua) -- A seminar on the water
quality, economy and technology in the upper reaches of the
Yangtze River was held here today.
</P>
<P>
Qian Zhengying, vice-chairwoman of the Chinese People's
Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC) National Committee, and
some other senior Chinese officials attended the seminar.
</P>
<P>
The seminar was jointly sponsored by the CPPCC Economic
Commission, a Japanese water conservancy research society studying
the Yangtze, and the Chongqing municipal government.
</P>
<P>
Participants discussed issues in the upper reaches
of the Yangtze River, such as water conservancy, environmental
protection, energy, the ecology, the prevention of soil erosion,
agriculture and sustainable social and economic development.
</P>
<P>
Japanese experts attending the meeting exhibited great interest
in building the Chongqing Hechuan Reservoir Project, a silt
control dam upstream the gigantic Three Gorges Power Project under
constuction.
</P>
<P>
Japan 13 years ago helped China build water conservancy
projects.
</P>
<P>
Now, it plans to introduce its advanced technology to help
develop the upper and middle reaches of the Yangtze River.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
