<HEADLINE> IRA Asks Britain to Do More on N.Irish Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The Irish Republican Army (IRA)
said today Britain must increase its efforts for a peaceful
settlement to the protracted conflict in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
A New Year message published in a newspaper of IRA's political
arm Sinn Fein said, "We reiterate our belief that all-party,
inclusive negotiations are crucial to the resolution of the
conflict between the British government and the Irish people."
</P>
<P>
"We leave 1997 behind, conscious that many nationalists are
impatient with the lack of progress in the negotiations process,"
said the outlawed IRA, which called a ceasefire with the British
government last July to enable Sinn Fein to attend the multi-party
peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The fragile peace process founded on talks and ceasefire is in
crisis, with Protestant loyalist extremists declaring their
opposition to the peace efforts.
</P>
<P>
Some pro-British paramilitary groups have resorted to violence,
killing two Catholic nationalists since Christmas after a loyalist
extremist leader was killed in Maze prison by dissident
republicans opposed to the peace process.
</P>
<P>
British Northern Ireland Secretary Mo Mowlam is going to meet
with both IRA and loyalist prisoners on Friday in a bid to
persuade them to support the peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
