<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Farrakhan Supports Zimbabwe's Land Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Visiting United States Nation of
Islam leader Louis Farrakhan today said Zimbabwe's land reform
policy was justified.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference on the first day of his visit to
Zimbabwe as part of his tour of 53 nations, Farrakhan said land
redistribution was proper provided it was done with equity and
without vengeance or evil intent.
</P>
<P>
"In the interest of the poor masses, in all equity and
fairness there should be land redistribution so that the poor
indigenous people can also grow and prosper," he said.
</P>
<P>
He added land redistribution was necessary because tracts of
land were seized from blacks during colonialism.
</P>
<P>
He said Zimbabwe was justified in asking Britain to fund the
land reform programme because most of its cities were built with
the wealth from Commonwealth nations.
</P>
<P>
British minister of state at the foreign and Commonwealth
office Tony Lloyd told journalists at the end of his two-day
visit to Zimbabwe on Wednesday his country had no direct
obligation to fund land reform in Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
The controversial Islamic leader also commended leaders of the
country's liberation struggle, president Robert Mugabe and
vice-president Joshua Nkomo, for their policy of reconciliation
which he said allowed whites to remain in Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
Farrakhan has so far visited 14 African countries on his peace
and reconciliation tour. 
</P>
</TEXT>
