<HEADLINE> Nepal Trains Midwives to Reduce Maternity Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Nepal has trained 1,500
midwives in the past years in efforts to reduce maternity and
child mortality rates in the country, the official RSS news agency
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The National Midwife Training Program aims to train 22,000
midwives by the year 2000, the RSS said.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that 44,000 Nepalese women die annually from
pregnancy or labor.
</P>
<P>
About 92 percent of child deliveries in Nepal take place at
home and an average Nepalese woman gives birth to five or six
babies during her life time, the RSS said.
</P>
<P>
A report entitled "Impact Assessment of Midwife Training"
issued Thursday said the trained midwives have been successful in
caring for lactating mothers and babies.
</P>
<P>
The report suggested that the training program be extended from
the targeted 59 districts to all the 75 districts in the country,
the RSS said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
