<HEADLINE> Zambian Rights Organization Worries Over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's human rights watchdog,
over the continued detention of the people connected with the
country's abortive military coup in 1997, Zambia News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
In a statement released in Lusaka this morning, the
commission's chairperson Judge Lombe Chibesakunda said 70 days
have passed since the first detentions were made but none of the
detainees have been charged or taken to court.
</P>
<P>
Local reports said over 90 people including former president
and opposition leader Kenneth Kaunda, have been detained for
alleged involvement in the coup under the state of emergency
declared by President Frederick Chiluba.
</P>
<P>
However, Kaunda was released from prison one week after he was
arrested last December and shifted to house arrest under a
presidential order.
</P>
<P>
Chibesakunda urged the detaining authorities to charge the
detainees and take them to court or release them.
</P>
<P>
She said the continued detention of restricted persons, though
lawful under the current state of emergency, is not conducive to
the building of a culture of human rights and democracy.
</P>
<P>
In the statement, Judge Chibesakunda also condemned the
harassment of both local and foreign journalists who have been
covering the case of Kaunda in the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
Journalists should be allowed to operate freely as they have a
duty to keep the nation informed, said the chairperson. 
</P>
</TEXT>
