<HEADLINE> Nearly 9,000 Hate Crimes Reported in U.S. in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Law enforcement agencies in
the United States reported 8,759 hate crimes taking place in 1996,
with race-motivated incidents accounting for more than 60 percent,
the Federal Bureau of Investigation said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Of the reported incidents, 5,396 was linked to racial bias,
1,401 to religious bias, 1,016 to sexual orientation bias, 940 to
ethnic bias and six to multiple biases.
</P>
<P>
"These statistics show what we long believed is true: hate
crimes have long gone under-reported," Attorney General Janet Reno
said at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
"Violent crime has dropped for five years in a row, but we're
just beginning to grasp the problem of hate crimes and how best to
fight back, and we are not going to let up," Reno said.
</P>
<P>
Reno said she has asked all 93 U.S. attorneys to appoint hate
crime coordinators to meet in Washington next month to map out
strategies to fight hate crimes.
</P>
<P>
The FBI first began reporting hate crime statistics in 1993.
</P>
</TEXT>
