<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany to Bug Suspected Criminals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, January 8 (Xinhua) -- German police will be allowed to
bug suspected criminals in combating the country's rising crime,
thanks to a deal reached late Wednesday between the German
government and major opposition Social Democrats (SPD), which is
expected to pass the parliament next week.
</P>
<P>
Under the legislation, which requires a change in the German
constitution, judges could approve police installing listening
devices in homes of suspects of serious crime, and of people who
might carry out major crimes, such as terrorism against the
public.
</P>
<P>
However, police would be barred from bugging conversations
between criminal suspects and religious figures or their lawyers.
The use of information bugged from doctors and lawyers would also
be limited.
</P>
<P>
The issue of police bugging has been debated in Germany for
years and such a need was made more acute only in the 1990s by
increasing organized and violent crime in the country.
</P>
<P>
Violent crime in Germany increased by 5.5 percent in 1996,
showed the latest available data. The number of crime cases
involving the use of firearms grew to 13,479 in 1996 from 12,855
in 1995.
</P>
<P>
German police launched 845 investigations into suspected
organized crime in 1996, compared to 787 in 1995. The economic
losses incurred by organized crime were estimated at 2.7 billion
marks (1.5 billion U.S. dollars) in 1996.  
</P>
</TEXT>
