<HEADLINE> 71 People Killed in Central Rwanda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Kigali, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Details continue to emerge about
Monday-Tuesday night "Interahamwe" militia's attack on two
communes of Central Gitarama Prefecture since the beginning of
this week.
</P>
<P>
The two communes where unrest has heightened these days are
Nyakabanda and Nyabikenke, located north of Gitarama town, on the
border with north-western Rwanda which is a fertile ground for
armed insurgency.
</P>
<P>
"Monday night militiamen armed with guns, machetes, and small
hoes raided 25 families, slaughtering 52 people, and seriously
wounding 8 others," local authorities in Nyakabanda told Rwanda
News Agency Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Four of those who were injured in the raid succumbed to the
wounds later on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
It had been earlier announced that only 26 persons had lost
their lives, but fresh reports put the number of victims at 56 in
this commune alone.
</P>
<P>
The attacks were mainly concentrated on Ngaru and Nuabinoni
"sectors" --adminitrative entities --- where they used small hoes
to kill villagers.
</P>
<P>
The list of the victims in Nyakabanda include notably 10 local
leaders, 17 children, and 6 mothers.
</P>
<P>
The militiamen who reportedly launched their attack from
Satinskyi in Gisenyi were assisted by many Hulu villagers from
that commune.
</P>
<P>
In neighbouring Nyabikenke, the militiamen killed 14 people
the same Monday night and wounded two others.
</P>
<P>
The commander of Gitarama-Kibuye Brigade, Col. Balthazar
Ndengeyinka, had told Rwanda News Agency on Wednesday that the
problems of insecurity in Central Gitarama are only localised in
three communes: Nyakabanda, Nyabikenke, and Dulinga.
</P>
<P>
All the three communes are on the extreme northern border of
Gitarama, in the vicinity of north-western Rwanda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
