<HEADLINE> U.S. to Review Its Policy towards Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 8 (Xinhua) -- In response to Iranian
President Mohammad Khatami's call for cultural exchanges, the
United States would review its policy toward Iran on exchanges
restrictions, the White House said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Mike McCurry told reporters that the
United States would review whether it is possible to lift visa
restrictions to allow exchanges of scholars and artists with
Iran.
</P>
<P>
"In the aftermath of President Khatami's interview last
night, that will be examined by the president's foreign policy
advisers. It is too soon to speculate on what, if any action
may result," he said.
</P>
<P>
President Khatami told CNN in an interview, broadcast on
Wednesday evening, that "nothing should prevent dialogue and
understanding between two nations, especially between their
scholars and thinkers."
</P>
<P>
"Right now, I recommend the exchange of professors, scholars,
writers, artists, journalists and tourists," he said in a
lengthy interview, which was seen as a message to the American
people.
</P>
<P>
McCurry welcomed Khatami's remarks, describing them as
"positive remarks about the United States."
</P>
<P>
"The president (Bill Clinton) appreciates those positive
remarks. We welcome the fact that he wants a dialogue with the
American people and between two great civilization. That can be
useful," he said.
</P>
<P>
But McCurry stressed the importance of direct contacts
between U.S. and Iranian governments.
</P>
<P>
"it's also important to stress that the best way for issues
to be addressed is for governments to talk directly," he said.
</P>
<P>
"As for the scope of any such dialogue, our views on that I
believe are very well known. But ultimately improvement in
relations depend upon not just what Iran says but what Iran
does," he repeated U.S. consistent stand toward Iran.
</P>
<P>
The United States said any improvement in relations between the
two countries, which severed following the 1979 Islamic
revolutions in Iran, could only result from addressing such issues
as Iran's supporting terrorism, developing of weapons of mass
destruction and interference in the Middle East peace process,
which President Khatami denied in his interview with CNN.
</P>
</TEXT>
