<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-08 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Divides Pullback Decision into Two </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu said today his government's decision on further
redeployment in the West Bank would be divided into two parts and
conditional on the Palestinian fulfillment of commitments.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu made the remarks at a meeting with heads of
coalition parties in a bid to rally support among hardliners to
the planned second phase of further redeployment. Rafael Eitan of
Tsomet, Aryeh Deri of Shas Party, Natan Sharansky of Israeli
Baaliya and Avigdor Khahalani of The Third Way were invited to the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said the pullback decision would be broken up into
two separate decisions.
</P>
<P>
He said the first decision on the scope of further pullback
would be made ahead of his scheduled trip to the United States
late this month.
</P>
<P>
Both Netanyahu and Palestinian National Authority (PNA)
President Yasser Arafat are to hold separate meetings in
Washington with U.S. President Bill Clinton to discuss advancing
the stalled peace process.
</P>
<P>
The second decision on the implementation of pullback would be
made months later based on the PNA's fulfillment of its
commitments, including fighting terrorism, amending the
Palestinian Covenant and extraditing Palestinian murderers.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu's new idea on the long-delayed pullback seemed to be
an attempt to further postpone the redeployment to appease the
hardliners within his rightwing government.
</P>
<P>
Due to this week's resignation of Foreign Minister David Levy,
a leading moderate within the rightwing coalition, Netanyahu's
maneuvering room has been dramatically reduced. A group of
rightist lawmakers have threatened to topple Netanyahu if he goes
ahead with the redeployment.
</P>
<P>
Many now doubt how Netanyahu could carry out the second
redeployment since his government has in fact become hostage of
the hardliners. Another dove within the government, Defense
Minister Yitzhak Mordechai, threatened Wednesday night to resign
if the government could not implement the pullback within three
months.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu late today held a third meeting with visiting
U.S. special peace envoy Dennis Ross. Under the heightened
U.S. pressure, Netanyahu repeatedly assured Washington that he
would honor the promise he made on the redeployment. But he is
reportedly scaling down the proposed percentage of pullback in the
West Bank from over 10 percent to 8 percent in order to gain
support from the hardliners.
</P>
<P>
The PNA has made it clear that it would firmly reject anything
that is less than 10 percent. In fact, the PNA has been demanding
for a 30 percent withdrawal in every stage of the three-phased
pullbacks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980109.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mass Strike by Eastern German Steelworkers Averted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, January 8 (Xinhua) -- A mass strike by eastern Germany's
steelworkers has been averted in the last minute after employers
conceded to a trade union's demand for wage parity between eastern
and western German steelworkers, German press reports said.
</P>
<P>
Under a compromise reached between eastern German steel
companies and the country's largest trade union IG Metall
Wednesday evening, employers have agreed to a 2.6 percent wage
hike for eastern Germany's 8,000 steelworkers for the period from
January this year to March 1999.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, each eastern German steelworker would also get a
one-time additional pay of 330 German marks (180 U.S. dollars) for
the period from October to December 1997.
</P>
<P>
While the IG Metall is hailing the deal as "a big victory for
the steelworkers", employers largely worried about the wage hike,
saying it had been agreed only under the threat of strike and
would risk the existence of eastern German steel companies with
about 80 percent of them already plagued by heavy losses at the
moment.
</P>
<P>
According to IG Metall's estimates, eastern German steelworkers
currently earn about 83 percent as much as their western German
fellow workers. But in the first half of 1997, each eastern German
steelworkers had produced about 250 tons of steel compared with
only 191 tons for a western German worker.
</P>
<P>
Employers however said that the productivity of the eastern
German steel industry was only about 77 percent of that in the
west. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980109.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
