<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OPEC Members Urged to Commit to Oil Quotas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The United Arab Emirates (UAE)
today called on members of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries (OPEC) to commit to their oil output quotas to shore up
world oil prices which have declined recently.
</P>
<P>
In a statement to UAE's Wam news agency, Minister of Oil and
Mineral Resources Obeid bin Saif Al Nasir said that over
production by OPEC members "would impose additional pressure" on
world oil prices.
</P>
<P>
"The flood of excessed production in oil markets will impose
additional pressure on world prices," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The current situation in oil markets demanded all OPEC
members to commit to their quotas to prevent the market from
being swamped by the flood," he said.
</P>
<P>
World oil prices began to go downhill after the OPEC decided in
November to increase its oil output ceiling from 24.1 million
barrels per day (bpd) to 27.5 million bpd this year.
</P>
<P>
The downward trend was accelerated during the last three months
when world oil prices dropped from 1997's averaged 19.43
U.S. dollars a barrel to this month's 15.9 dollars a barrel.
</P>
<P>
The oil price collapse was further deepened by other factors
including the over supply and the slackened world demand due to a
currency crisis spreading in Asia since the end of October, 1997.
</P>
<P>
The Asian region accounts for a quarter of world oil demand and
over the past five years has contributed to nearly 50 percent of
the global growth in crude demand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980109.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-08 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 4 Israeli Soldiers Wounded in South Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Four Israeli soldiers and two
members of South Lebanese Army (SLA), the Israeli militia ally
were wounded this afternoon by a roadside bomb donated by Lebanese
guerillas, local radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The Voice of People said that the country's Islamic resistance
movement had claimed responsibility for the explosion.
</P>
<P>
A statement released by the movement said guerillas donated
the bomb at 2:12 p.m. local time (12:12 GMT) when an Israeli
patrol was travelling on the Heni-Yibel road in the central sector
of the Israeli self-proclaimed security zone in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The radio said its reporter inside the security zone witnessed
the explosion and described the sound of it as "very loud."
</P>
<P>
In retaliation for guerillas' attack, Israeli artillery fired
about 30 mortar rounds on the outskirts of several villages near
the explosion site.
</P>
<P>
The tit-for-tat conflict between Israeli troops and Lebanese
guerillas has lasted for more than 10 years since Israel carved
out a 1,200-square-kilometer area in south Lebanon as the
security zone to protect its northern towns from cross-border
attacks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
