<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PNA Criticizes Israel's Settlement Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) today strongly criticized Israel's plan to build
new housing units in Efrat, a town near Bethlehem in the West
Bank, for Jewish settlers.
</P>
<P>
PNA Higher Education Minister Hanan Ashrawi told Israel Radio
today that the planned construction of new housing units for
Jewish settlers in Efrat "is a serious blow to the American
efforts to revive the peace process."
</P>
<P>
"This new housing plan showed Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
is determined to destroy the peace process before his government
is finished," she said.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli government on Wednesday approved construction of
574 housing units in Efrat, in defiance of a U.S. call for "time
out" on settlement expansion.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israel's Meretz Party and the peace movement "Peace
Now" also criticized this plan today.
</P>
<P>
Meretz leader Yossi Sarid said that the new housing
construction plan is an obstacle to the peace process which could
trigger confrontations with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Ran Cohen, a Knesset (parliament) member of Meretz, also said
that the government's decision to build more housing units in
Efrat is an economic scandal.
</P>
<P>
He asked why the government agreed to allocate about 2 million
U.S. dollars to build more houses for the well-placed population
in Efrat while thousands of other families are waiting for
solutions of their housing problems.
</P>
<P>
The "Peace Now" pointed out that the new housing plan in Efrat
was the third of the type adopted by the government recently aimed
at expanding Jewish settlements, not for the natural population
growth as claimed by the government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
