<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ECOWAS Urges S. Leone Junta to Abide by Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The Economic Community of West
African States (ECOWAS) today urged the military regime in Sierra
Leone to respect the peace plan to end the country's crisis,
restating that the deadline of April 22 this year for the junta
to quit remains unchanged.
</P>
<P>
At a news briefing here this afternoon, Adrienne Yande Diop,
Information Director of the ECOWAS executive secretary, also
called for the strengthening of sanctions against the junta.
</P>
<P>
According to Yande Diop, the ECOWAS committee of five on
Sierra Leone has reiterated that the peace plan signed between it
and the junta in Conakry, Guinea, last October remained the best
framework for the restoration of peace and constitutional order.
</P>
<P>
The peace accord provided for, among other things, the
immediate cessation of hostilities, the reinstatement of Kabbah's
government within six months, disarmament, demobilization and
reintegration of combatants beginning last december, and
humanitarian assistance.
</P>
<P>
However, the junta said later that it would not step down
according to the schedule because of the delay in disarmament and
the arrival of international aids.
</P>
<P>
At its latest meeting on December 19 last year, the committee
accused the junta's move of disrupting the peace process in S.
Leone.
</P>
<P>
Foreign ministers from Nigeria, Ghana, Guinea, Cote d'Ivoire
and Liberia noted the junta's violations of the ECOWAS and
U.N.sanctions, especially of arms embargo and travel
restrictions, Diop said.
</P>
<P>
They also deplored the junta's upgrading of an airstrip into a
full-fledged airport for the illegal importation of arms and
other supplies, as well as its unprovoked attacks on the ECOWAS
peacekeeping force known as ECOMOG.
</P>
<P>
"ECOMOG has to retaliate," she added.
</P>
<P>
On what steps the committee is to take to deal with the latest
developments in Sierra Leone, the information director said,
"It's only a few weeks. You have to take time to see the
progress."
</P>
<P>
To enhance the operational capacity of ECOMOG, Nigeria has
recently deployed more troops to Sierra Leone, and Ghana has also
sent a vessel to join the ECOMOG fleet.
</P>
<P>
Diop stressed the junta's reluctance would not affect the
determination of west African countries to resolve the crisis
there because "peace and security is a pre-requisite for
the sub-region."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
