<HEADLINE> EU to Send Fact-Finding Delegation to Algeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) decided
here today in principle to send a fact-finding delegation to
Algeria, where a series of killings have been reported recently.
</P>
<P>
British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook, whose country is holding
the rotating the EU presidency, said in a statement that the EU
delegation would include representatives from the current EU
president Britain, the outgoing president Luexmbourg and next EU
president Austria.
</P>
<P>
"We now have agreement in principle with our EU partners that a
troika mission at official level should visit Algeria," Cook said.
</P>
<P>
"It will also enable the EU to make clear to the Algerian
government the concern felt in Europe about the security situation
in Algeria and our desire to offer humanitarian assistance," he
added.
</P>
<P>
British government officials said that no concrete timetable
has been made about the EU visit, but EU officials had been in
touch with the Algerian government.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that some 1,000 Algerian civilians have been
killed in the first few days of the holy Moslem month of Ramamdan.
</P>
</TEXT>
