<HEADLINE> Israeli Woman Posting Pig Leaflets Gets Two Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The Jerusalem District Court
today sentenced Tatiana Susskin, who posted leaflets depicting the
Muslim Prophet Muhammad as a pig, to two years in prison plus
another year's suspended term.
</P>
<P>
Susskin, convicted late December of racism, threatening public
order and supporting extremist Jewish group, could face a
sentence of up to 26 years. But the court handed down the
relatively light sentence, citing she is not totally well
mentally.
</P>
<P>
Susskin, 26, from Jerusalem, was arrested in June after
posting the pig leaflets on the storefronts of Arab shops in the
West Bank city of Hebron. The leaflets sparked angry Muslim
protests worldwide and Palestinian violence in the territories.
</P>
<P>
During the trial, her defense lawyers had tried to convince the
court that she was too mentally ill to control her own actions.
</P>
<P>
But the court rejected the defense's argument and put her on
trial. Still, the court apparently took into consideration of her
mental state.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the posting of the leaflets, Susskin was also
found having committed other crimes against Arabs, such as
throwing stones at Palestinian cars and supporting the outlawed
Jewish extremist group the Kach Movement. While posting the pig
leaflets, she was wearing a yellow sweater bearing the Kach's
symbol of clenched fists.
</P>
<P>
By giving the sentence, the court said it was issuing a
message that Israel could not tolerate extremist actions, which
insulted Muslim not only in Israel but all over the world.
</P>
<P>
Susskin repeated that she had no regret for what she had done,
because she did it for her love of Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
