<HEADLINE> Addis Ababa Residents Urged to Curb Rabies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Addis Ababa residents were
today appealed to get their dogs regularly vaccinated in a bid to
curb the spread of rabies.
</P>
<P>
The call was made by Yosef Bagafe, Team Coordinator of
veterinary disease research section of the National Health and
Nutrition Research Institute of Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
According to a report here today, Yosef said that more than
800 people in the city were bitten by rabid dogs in the past four
months, and among them five individuals lost their lives to
rabies.
</P>
<P>
Bagafe said that the number of people in Addis Ababa attacked
by rabid dogs is on the rise more than ever. The existence of a
great number of stray dogs in the capital has been the major
reason behind this tragic incident, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
