<HEADLINE> Most European Shares down on Weak Dow, Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Most of the major stock markets
in Europe extended Wednesday's losses and ended sharply lower
Thursday, with London the only exception and rising marginally.
</P>
<P>
Britain's leading shares closed 0.3 percent or 13 points higher
at 5,237.1 but well below the day's highs after gains were capped
by a fresh fall on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of England's decision today to keep rates on hold came
as no surprise, but some experts believe they will have to go up
shortly to stop the economy from overheating.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that there was still plenty of institutional cash
lined up to go into the market.
</P>
<P>
German shares ended on a weaker note as the dollar slipped
below 1.83 German mark and concerns about Asian turmoil depressed
the market. The DAX-30 index fell by 44.31 points to close at
4,347.23.
</P>
<P>
In Paris, the CAC-40 index also closed down for the third
session in a row, hit by a slump in the banking sector, concerns
about Asia and fresh weakness on Wall Street. The index ended at
2,954.94, down 51.79 points or 1.72 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
