<HEADLINE> UK to Urge for New EU Development Targets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Britain, the current European
Union (EU) president, pledged here today to urge its EU partners
to incorporate international development targets into the
15-nation bloc's aid program.
</P>
<P>
After meeting the EU Commissioners responsible for overseas
development here this afternoon, Britain's International
Development Secretary Clare Short said that a special seminar
would be held in Brussels in March to discuss the targets.
</P>
<P>
"By working together, the EU can make a significant
contribution to poverty eradication in developing countries,"
Short said in a statement after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Short noted that the Commissioners also agreed the EU's
Development Council in May will discuss the poverty focus and
gender equality in its development assistance.
</P>
<P>
She stressed that another priority for Britain's six-month
presidency included agreeing the EU's mandate for negotiating the
successor to the Lome Convention, which regulates the EU's aid,
trade and political relationship with 71 former colonies in
Africa, the Caribbean and Pacific. 
</P>
</TEXT>
