<HEADLINE> Kaunda Denies Involvement in Coup Attempt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Zambian former President Kenneth
Kaunda denied here today that he was directly or indirectly
involved in the october abortive coup.
</P>
<P>
He said in Lusaka High Court that he has always condemned
military coups and that he did not hesitate to condemn the
October 28 coup attempt.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda said that he believes in non-violent struggle.
</P>
<P>
He said military coups could bring unending sufferings to the
Zambian people.
</P>
<P>
He said that all those African countries which experienced
military coups in the past have never been stable. He cited
Sudan, Somali, Rwanda and Nigeria as some of the examples.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda stressed that as a matter of principle there is no way
he could be involved in a coup.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda was arrested on December 25 last year in alleged
connection with the October 28 abortive coup and transferred from
prison to house arrest on December 31. 
</P>
</TEXT>
