<HEADLINE> Labor's Dewar Ready to Stand for Scottish Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Britain's Scottish Secretary
Donald Dewar said today he decided to stand for election to the
new Scottish Parliament.
</P>
<P>
Dewar, 60, is known as the principal architect of the "yes"
campaign in the recent referendum in Scotland. The parliament will
have wide powers in key areas of Scottish life such as health,
education, agriculture and the environment.
</P>
<P>
By announcing his decision, Dewar said in a statement: "The
relationship with the Government of the United Kingdom will be
crucial. The new parliament must earn the confidence of Scots."
</P>
<P>
As Labor is the dominant political party in Scotland, the
leader of its parliamentary group is virtually certain to become
First Minister.
</P>
<P>
The chances of Dewar getting this job increased earlier this
week when Foreign Secretary Robin Cook, tipped as a likely
candidate, said he planned to remain in his present post.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Tony Blair welcomed Dewar's decision. He said at
a news conference he believed that "by going and standing for the
Scottish Parliament, and by exercising his leadership qualities
there, he will enhance both the Scottish Parliament and the whole
British political system." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
