<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-08 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Survey: Majority of Israelis, Palestinians Support </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The majority of both Israelis
and Palestinians support the Oslo process, while the Israelis tend
to put more blame for impending the process on themselves than the
Palestinians, said a public opinion survey.
</P>
<P>
The survey, issued here Thursday evening, was jointly conducted
by the Jerusalem Media and Communication Center and Tami Steinmetz
Center for Peace Research of Tel Aviv University in the last two
months of 1997.
</P>
<P>
A total of 1,185 Palestinians aged 18 and over and 1,002
Israelis of the same age were interviewed during the survey, with
the Palestinians being interviewed face-to-face, while the
Israelis answered questionaires through telephone.
</P>
<P>
As for the attitude towards the peace process, 59 percent
of the Israeli respondents support it, which is slightly lower
than the 68 percent in the Palestinian respondents, the survey
said.
</P>
<P>
Similarly, the survey said, 59 percent of Palestinian and 62.5
percent of Israeli respondents are optimistic about the prospects
of concluding a peace accord between Israel and the Palestinian
National Authority (PNA).
</P>
<P>
On the question of the obstacle facing the peace process,
almost all Palestinian respondents referred to factors on the
Israeli side, such as Israeli intransigence (27 percent),
settlement activities (17 percent), Israel's Likud government (10
percent) and the Jerusalem issue (7 percent).
</P>
<P>
On the same question, 27 percent of the Israeli respondents
blamed the Israeli government and Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu for blocking the four-year-old Oslo peace process,
while 9 percent of them said the obstacle is terrorism.
</P>
<P>
On the question of personal security, 64 percent of the
Palestinians said there is an improvement in this regard since
the process began, but 55 percent of the Israelis said there is no
change.
</P>
<P>
As for expectations to peace, 65 percent of the Palestinian and
77 percent of Israeli respondents believe that they should
strengthen their support for peace, and relations in all fields
between the two peoples should be strengthened too.
</P>
<P>
The two groups also hold similar views on the need to have a
clear demarcated border between the two sides, with 63 percent of
the Palestinian and 81 percent of the Israeli respondents favoring
such a separation, the survey said.
</P>
<P>
On the question of assessing the other side's intentions, 89
percent of the Palestinian respondents believe that the Israeli
government does not want peace. The Israelis are of two minds
concerning the PNA, 56 percent of them believe the PNA is truly
interested in peace and 40 percent believe to the contrary.
</P>
<P>
Despite the asymmetry in the two peoples' situation and the
difference, the survey found a large majority of Israelis (70
percent) and Palestinians (73 percent) deem themselves "very
optimistic" or "optimistic" concerning the future generally.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980109.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Allows Limited Partnership of Foreign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia today agreed on
the limited partnership of foreign investors in the defense
industry, power generation and telecom sector, the Ethiopian News
Agency said.
</P>
<P>
The limited participation of private investors in these
sectors was suggested in a key-note address by Ethiopian Prime
Minister Meles Zenawi at the ruling party conference opened
yesterday in Jimma Town, some 340 kms away of Addis Ababa.
</P>
<P>
Participants at the third regular conference of the ruling
Ethiopian People's Revolutionary Democratic Front (EPRDF)
expressed the belief that the involvement of the entrepreneurs
would help the enhancement of the on-going rural centered
development strategy, the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
After a thorough discussion on the issue, participants have
agreed on the limited involvement of foreign investors in the
telecom sector which demands huge funds for its expansion thus
hindering competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
With regard to tapping energy resources, the conference
accepted participation of foreign entrepreneurs in power
generation alone, leaving the supply and distribution to the
government, since it will be difficult to properly exploit the
potential the nation has in the sector due to capacity
limitations.
</P>
<P>
The participants also have agreed that some
of the defense industries under the auspices of the Ministry of
Defense, which could not operate through the use of local civil
resources alone, should begin producing mainly goods meant for
civil purpose through the involvement of foreign investors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
