<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 65 Million Dollars Raised by Diana Tribute Album </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 8 (Xinhua) -- A Princess Diana tribute album by
the world's top music stars has raised 65 million U.S. dollars for
her favored charities.
</P>
<P>
Richard Branson, responsible for the fund raising, said today
that "the music industry worked together like never before" by
raising so much money in just four weeks.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-six well-known singers from different countries, ranging
from Michael Jackson to Luciano Pavarotti, contributed to the
compilation record after Princess Diana died in a car crash
incident on August 31 of last year.
</P>
<P>
One million copies have been sold in Britain, and another 3
million around the world, Branson said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
British famous singer Elton John's "Candle in the Wind," sung
at Diana's funeral, became the world's biggest-selling single
within a month of its September release.
</P>
<P>
Record producers believe that combined sales from the single
and the compilation album could top 100 million pounds -- twice
what Bob Geldof earned with his 1985 pop benefit concert for
African famine relief.
</P>
<P>
The official Princess Diana Memorial Fund set up its own record
label to ensure that all profits go directly to her favored
charities, which range from AIDS to land-mine victims and the
homeless. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
