<HEADLINE> Turkey Launches Investigation into Illegal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Interior Minister Murat
Baseskioglu today ordered an extensive investigation into the
massive wave of illegal immigration to Italy, local TV reports
said.
</P>
<P>
Baseskioglu said that those organizers of the refugee
smuggling would be punished under the laws.
</P>
<P>
"An inspection commission composed of administrative and police
officials is now in charge of the investigation. If necessary,
additional officials from the relevant ministries will join them,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Large numbers of Kurds from southeastern Turkey and northern
Iraq were transported through different ways to Italy since
last week, causing grave concern in Turkey, Italy as well as some
European countries.
</P>
<P>
Turkish police had tightened security measures in the largest
city of Istanbul and other harbor cities in an effort to stop more
immigrants from illegally heading for Italy.
</P>
<P>
Dozens of immigration organizers and hundreds of Kurds trying
to flee Turkey had been detained in Istanbul, local press reports
said.
</P>
<P>
Baseskioglu called for international coordination in handling
this large-scale illegal immigration since some people are from
neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
About 196 illegal Bangladeshi immigrants who were trying to go
to Europe via Turkey were freed Thursday by Turkish police, a
spokesman from the Bangladeshi Embassy in Ankara said.
</P>
<P>
Italy has said that it will grant some of the Kurds political
asylum if they are proved to face political prosecution in their
places, which angered Turkey and Germany.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Foreign Ministry spokesman Sermet Atacanli said earlier
that these Kurds fled their home to seek a better life in rich
European countries, stressing that this had nothing to do with
the alleged human rights issue.
</P>
<P>
Germany, which has a population of nearly half a million
Kurds, accused Italy of adopting an open-door policy on this
issue, saying that this would possibly lead to a new wave of
Kurdish immigration to Germany.
</P>
<P>
Police heads from Turkey and six European countries gathered in
Rome Thursday to discuss how to deal with the current wave of
illegal immigration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
