<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-08 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Voices Support for Turkey's EU Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, January 8 (Xinhua) -- French Foreign Minister Hubert
Vedrine today reiterated his country's support of Turkey's bid for
full European Union (EU) membership, the Anatolia News Agency said.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine, who arrived here Wednesday on a one-day visit, made
the statement during his meeting with Turkish President Suleyman
Demirel.
</P>
<P>
He said that France would do its utmost to help Turkey achieve
its goal of becoming a full EU member country.
</P>
<P>
The minister, however, admitted that no country could forcibly
impose its will on the EU policy-making process, indicating that
Turkey has to make energetic efforts by itself.
</P>
<P>
"I am not an EU representative or envoy," Vedrine affirmed
repeatedly while answering reporters' questions.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine is the first minister of the EU countries to visit
Ankara since Turkey announced last month its suspension of
political dialog with the European bloc following its exclusion
from the EU enlargement process.
</P>
<P>
The French foreign minister also hoped that Turkey would send
a delegation to an EU meeting scheduled for March in London aimed
at discussing the details of the upcoming accession talks.
</P>
<P>
Turkey had stated that it would not participate in the London
meeting because of the EU discriminative attitude regarding
Turkey's membership bid.
</P>
<P>
The EU invitation of some eastern European countries and
Cyprus to the enlargement process has angered Ankara, which
claimed that some of these countries had poorer conditions
compared with that of Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The EU has always held that Turkey has to take pains to
improve its poor human rights record before being invited to the
membership talks.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine also held talks with his Turkish counterpart Ismail
Cem earlier today, exchanging views on the ways of furthering
bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Both foreign ministers agreed on the forming of a think tank
which aims to maintain routine contacts between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
They also discussed the possibility of President Suleyman
Demirel's state visit to Paris in mid-February. 
</P>
</TEXT>
