<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ECOWAS 1998 Programs Stick to Integration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The Economic Community of West
African States (ECOWAS) said today it will continue to undertake
programs aimed at promoting sub-regional integration and
development.
</P>
<P>
The areas that will catch the attention of ECOWAS this year
include trade, customs, tourism, transport, telecommunications,
energy and social and cultural affairs, ECOWAS information
director Adrienne Yande Diop disclosed at a news briefing here
this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The 16-member ECOWAS was established in 1975 as a sub-regional
economic bloc aimed at promoting development through economic
integration.
</P>
<P>
A lot of protocols have been signed to this effect and the
first of them is on the free movement of persons within member
countries.
</P>
<P>
Despite the gained achievements, problems remain as many of
the protocols are either waiting for some member states to ratify
or faced with hitches in implementation.
</P>
<P>
Even Travelers of one member countries with proper documents
to other countries are frequently harassed at immigration and
customs offices due to lack of knowledge of both the travelers
and the officers on free movement, according to Diop.
</P>
<P>
The information director also decried the ill-implementation
of the protocol on membership contribution, the financial source
of the ECOWAS executive secretariat.
</P>
<P>
The Head of States of some member countries often forgot the
documents they had signed, leading to irregular and non-payment
of financial dues to the community, she claimed.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics, the member states owe the
sub-regional organization a total of 44.7 million U.S. Dollars.
Some of them have not paid their contribution for more than 10
years.
</P>
<P>
The secretariat therefore decided to embark on an
enlightenment campaign this year designed to inform the people on
their rights and responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
This is especially to promote travel within the sub-region and
check undue harassment by immigration and customs officials.
</P>
<P>
Work will continue to complete the trans-Sahelian highway from
Dakar, Senegal to Ndjamena, Chad, and the trans-coastal road from
Lagos, Nigeria to Nouakchott, Mauritania.
</P>
<P>
Both roads have been more than 85 percent completed.
</P>
<P>
The information director announced that the second ECOWAS
trade fair will be held in Accra, Ghana next month in a fresh
effort to promote trade among member states.
</P>
<P>
The first such event took place three years ago in Dakar.
</P>
<P>
Beside, the secretariat will undertake the organization of the
first ECOWAS tourism fair in Abidjan, Cote d'Ivoire this year,
she said.
</P>
<P>
Efforts will also be made for the complete harmonization of
documents, regulations and custom formalities, as well as in
collective drug war.
</P>
<P>
In the field of social and cultural affairs, Diop said this
year's ECOWAS prize for excellence would be in literature.
Competition was in the field of pharmacopoeia last year.
</P>
<P>
The director did not forget to mention the work in the
information department, saying that ECOWAS has been in lack of
good communication to inform the world of what it has done for
many years.
</P>
<P>
She said one of the most important things is to go to
computerization and Internet so that everyone with a computer and
access to the international information network can easily get to
know the progress of ECOWAS.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
