<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Ruling Party Pledges to Continue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 8 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's ruling
African National Congress (ANC) today celebrated its 86th
anniversary, vowing to continue its struggle for fundamental
social transformation.
</P>
<P>
New ANC president Thabo Mbeki said at the party's anniversary
celebrations here that the ANC had helped build a better life for
all South Africans, and would continue on this path.
</P>
<P>
More people in South Africa now had access to health care,
more children had entered the school system and many homes, in
both rural and urban areas, had been electrified, said Mbeki, who
is also deputy president of the country.
</P>
<P>
The ANC leader, however, pointed out that not as much progress
had been achieved as the party had hoped. He stressed the need to
wage a determined struggle to overcome the terrible legacy of
apartheid which continued to define the nature of society.
</P>
<P>
South Africans need to be realistic and acknowledge that three
decades of apartheid damage could not be undone in three years of
democratic rule, Mbeki noted.
</P>
<P>
The black-dominated ANC took state power in May 1994 which saw
the first non-racial general elections in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
referring to crime issues, Mbeki pledged that his party would
do its best to root out crimes.
</P>
<P>
South Africa could not say it had attained a good quality of
life for all its citizens as long as it continued to allow crime,
the party chief said.
</P>
<P>
"Not only must we work to ensure that the people do not do
crime, we must also strive to ensure that they do not tolerate
it," Mbeki noted.
</P>
<P>
On world issues, Mbeki said that his party would continue to
strive to build a society which would contribute to the creation
of a better world order.
</P>
<P>
South Africa would act in solidarity with the people of
Palestine and peoples of other countries in addressing challenges
facing them, Mbeki said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
