<HEADLINE> Nigerian Children Severely Malnourished </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 8 (Xinhua) -- A Nigerian scientist today painted a
gloomy picture of rising poverty in the country, saying that 87
percent of the child population in the country is severely malnourished.
</P>
<P>
According to Tunde Ajayi, acting Director of Nigerian Institute for
Oceanography and Marine Research (NIOMR), 35 percent of children under
five were under-weight, 43 percent stunted and nine percent wasted,
leaving only 13 percent of the juvenile population wholesome and
healthy.
</P>
<P>
Ahayi made the disclosure at the second review and planning meeting
of the nationally-coordinated research program in marine fisheries
held here today.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the problem to poor dietary protein supply, noting
that the trend had also made children to suffer both physical and
material devastation, the News Agency of Nigeria reported.
</P>
<P>
According to the scientist, researchers have focused on intergrated
fish, poultry, piggery and vegetable production to meet the country's
protein requirements.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, fisheries society of Nigeria President Sam Talabi has
criticized the lifting of the embargo on importation of frozen chicken
under the newly released 1998 government budget, saying that it would
adversely affect fish production in the country.
</P>
<P>
The President noted that fish production had been low in the
country that the government had to spend up to 20 billion Naira (about
250 million U.S. Dollars) on fish importation every year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
