<HEADLINE> Kenyan President Names New Cabinet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Newly re-elected Kenyan
President Daniel Arap Moi today announced the list of a new
cabinet excluding the vice president.
</P>
<P>
Simeon Nyachae will replace Musalia Mudavadi as new Finance
Minister, according to a statement from the Presidential Press
Services (PPS).
</P>
<P>
Former Foreign Minister Kalonzo Musyoka moved to the Education
Ministry and was replaced by Bonaya Godana, the former Deputy
Speaker of parliament.
</P>
<P>
Nicholas Biwott and Jackson Kalweo, former key ministers in
the president's office, have been given their own departments to
run and are replaced by Marsden Madoka and Gideon Ndambuki.
</P>
<P>
"I have spent many hours to decide who, among the elected
representatives of wananchi (the broad masses) will assist me in
managing the affairs of our beloved nation," Moi said in the
statement.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet list showed sweeping changes after 12 members of
Moi's 25-strong cabinet failed to win their parliamentary seats
in the just-ended general elections.
</P>
<P>
Local analysts said that the lack of a vice-president
suggested a power struggle within the ruling Kenya African
National Union (KANU) had still not been resolved.
</P>
<P>
KANU had its parliamentary majority significantly reduced in
last week's elections with many of the party faithful complaining
that its queue system of nominating would-be MPs had
disenfranchised supporters.
</P>
<P>
Moi, 73 and in power since 1978, won a fifth and final
five-year term in last week's elections while KANU won 106
parliamentary seats against the combined opposition's 104.
</P>
<P>
A further 12 lawmakers will be appointed according to elected
party strength in the national assembly.
</P>
<P>
There are no women in Moi's cabinet, but he has formed a new
ministry to deal with women's and youth affairs. Its minister is
Maalim Mohamed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
