<HEADLINE> Pakistan Likely to Increase Sugar Export </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan has the prospect of
exporting more than 300,000 tons of sugar worth about 100 million
U.S. dollars this year, sources from the sugar industry said on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Negotiations have begun with various international buyers to
sell sugar at the London Commodity Exchange, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan's sugar industry is likely to produce 3.2 million tons
of sugar this year as the country had a bumper sugarcane crop of
about 52 million tons last year.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the sugar industry has a sufficient held-up stock
of sugar at the mills, leaving at least 600,000 to 800,000 tons of
sugar for export after meeting the domestic demand of 2.8 million
tons.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Commerce Minister Ishaq Dar has indicated that the
government may consider allowing 200,000 tons of sugar to be
exported in addition to the existing limit of 300,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
The Economic Coordination Committee (ECC) recently gave
approval for exporting 300,000 tons of sugar.
</P>
<P>
Talking to the local media Friday, Dar said the government now
would maintain the restriction of sugar export at 300,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
"But it can be increased to 500,000 tons subject to the actual
figure of its production," he added.  
</P>
