<HEADLINE> U.S. Consumer Electronics Sale to Boom in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAS VEGAS, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Sales of home information
products will outpace sales of home entertainment products in the
United States in 1998, the Consumer Electronics Manufacturers
Association (CEMA) said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"While home entertainment continues to be an important segment
of the consumer electronics industry, home information has become
the largest and fastest growing product group," CEMA President
Gary Shapiro said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
He said the home information product, including personal
computers, modems, printers, monitors and cordless phones will
generate sales of 34.5 billion U.S. dollars this year.
</P>
<P>
Combining home entertainment products such as TV sets, digital
versatile disc and audio products, sales of consumer electronics
products will grow 5 percent to a record 75.6 billion dollars in
1998, said the CEMA, organizer of the International Consumer
Electronics Show which opened here earlier Thursday.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,800 makers of such consumer electronics as stereos,
TV sets, phones, Internet products, cameras, video cameras and
home theater systems are parading their wares at the show with
more than 100,000 attendees expected.
</P>
<P>
Digital products, including digital television, digital cameras
and digital versatile disc, take an important position at the show.
</P>
<P>
The CEMA estimated that factory sales of consumer electronics
products will reach 92 billion dollars in 2001. 
</P>
</TEXT>
