<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Balloonists Launch Nonstop Round-World Trip </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Two U.S. balloonists launched
a 52-meter silver balloon into the sky earlier this morning in New
Mexico to bid to make aviation history by circling the globe
without stopping.
</P>
<P>
Dick Rutan, 59, and Dave Melton, 39, floated the ball-shaped
Global Hilton balloon into the clear pre-dawn sky with wind about
9 kph out of the southeast.
</P>
<P>
The liftoff came three days after weather conditions forced a
delay.
</P>
<P>
The Global Hilton is a combination hot-air balloon and helium
balloon, with 18 propane tanks to fuel the flames that warm the
gas. It was planned to rise immediately 9,700 meters into the jet
stream and ride 300 kph air currents around the world in about 14
days.
</P>
<P>
As the balloon's white capsule is pressurized, it can safely
fly at high altitudes in strong wind currents.
</P>
<P>
Rutan is a former Air Force pilot from Mojave, California, who
helped fly the experimental plane Voyager around the world nonstop
11 years ago. Melton has three time of balloon experiences.
</P>
<P>
It was the third such attempt by a balloon team to circle the
globe since December 31.
</P>
<P>
Chicago millionaire Steve Fossett ended his fourth
round-the-world bid Monday when he landed on the edge of the Black
Sea.
</P>
<P>
Fossett had hoped to break his own record of traveling 10,361
miles in a balloon in six days and two and a half hours set in
January 1997.
</P>
<P>
Another balloonist, Kevin Uliassi, left Loves Park, Illinois,
on New Year's Eve but an equipment problem forced him to land a
few hours later in Indiana. 
</P>
</TEXT>
