<DOCNO> XIE19980109.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New HIV/AIDS Intervention Measures Gain International Support </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Funding from governments and
organizations from overseas will enable Chinese AIDS control
experts to carry out a number of new programs, including promoting
the use condoms and publishing literature on AIDS to enhance the
awareness of primary school students.
</P>
<P>
Some 100 plans for blocking the further spread of acquired
immune deficiency syndrome (AIDS) in China have been submitted to
representatives from more than 40 foreign embassies and
international organizations with the means to provide financial
and technological support.
</P>
<P>
The programs included establishing an Internet HIV/AIDS
information center, promoting the use of condoms amongst high-risk
groups, and publishing textbooks about sex and AIDS for school
children.
</P>
<P>
"The programs will undoubtedly help China curb the HIV/AIDS
epidemic. However, the major problem centers on the lack of
technology and capital," according to Liu Peilong, director of
Department of International Cooperation under the Ministry of
Health (MOH). Liu made the remarks today during the International
Donor's Meeting on HIV/AIDS Control in China.
</P>
<P>
China documented 8,303 cases of human immunodeficiency virus
(HIV) by the end of October 1997, with 209 cases involving fully
developed AIDS and an additional 119 cases involving death.
</P>
<P>
However, experts estimated that the country had between
150,000-200,000 HIV cases by the end of 1996.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese government is fully prepared to the international
community in a concerted effort to battle HIV/AIDS," according to
State Councillor Peng Peiyun.
</P>
<P>
Developers of the related programs joined foreign diplomats and
representatives from the European Union, The Ford Foundation, the
United Nations Development Program (UNDP) and various other
organizations today in discussions of the feasibility of proposed
project.
</P>
<P>
Implementation of said programs will enable China to make
progress in developing omnidirectional projects, raise the level
of public awareness concerning AIDS prevention and control issues,
guarantee safety in health care settings and improve care for
people suffering from HIV/AIDS, according to Liu.
</P>
<P>
An effective and scientific surveillance system will be created
and community participation in all aspects of HIV programs will be
enhanced, said Liu.
</P>
<P>
The goal of the meeting was to "strengthen the international
community's awareness of the HIV/AIDS situation in China and
promote greater participation in control efforts", and to "ensure
all possible international support will be forthcoming," according
to Arthur Holcombe, resident coordinator of UN operational
activities in China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
