<HEADLINE> Five Nepali Ministers Resign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Five Nepali cabinet ministers
tendered their resignations Friday as Nepali Prime Minister Surya
Bahadur Thapa waited for King Birendra's decision on his proposal
to hold mid-term polls, state-run radio said.
</P>
<P>
King Birendra has accepted the resignations submitted to the
prime minister by Defense Minister Fateh Singh Tharu, Minister for
Science and Technology Rajiv Parajuli and three ministers without
portfolio, Radio Nepal said.
</P>
<P>
The resignations come as no surprise as the five ministers, all
from Thapa's own National Democratic Party (RPP), have joined
hands with the opposition Communist Party of Nepal (United
Marxism-Leninism, CPN-UML) in initiating a no-confidence motion
against the present coalition government.
</P>
<P>
These ministers plus 87 MPs from the CPN-UML on Thursday
requested the King to convene a special session of the parliament
to discuss their no-confidence motion.
</P>
<P>
To preempt the move, Thapa on Thursday asked the King to
dissolve parliament and hold mid-term polls.
</P>
<P>
King Birendra has been consulting with his advisors and former
prime ministers about the situation in the country, but no
decision has been made yet, sources here said.
</P>
<P>
Thapa came to power on October 7, 1997 as the head of a
three-party coalition formed by the Nepali Congress, the RPP and
the Nepal Sadbhavana Party.  
</P>
</TEXT>
