<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Publishes HIV/AIDS Figures  (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 9 (Xinhua) -- China had documented 8,303 cases
of human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) by the end of October 1997,
with 209 cases involving fully developed acquired immune
deficiency syndrome (AIDS) and 119 patients having died from the
disease.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Health (MOH) released the figures today, and
vowed to control the epidemic level at under 1.5 million cases by
the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
"The spread of HIV/AIDS entered into a period of rapid growth,
namely HIV infections resulting from sexual activity and contact
with contaminated blood, as well as infant HIV infection,
according to Minister of Health Chen Minzhang.
</P>
<P>
Intravenous drug use accounted for 5,495 cases, with additional
547 HIV/AIDS cases resulting from heterosexual
contacts. Homosexual behavior and the using contaminated blood
products were also held responsible for a limited number of cases.
</P>
<P>
The ration of male to female HIV/AIDS patients stood at
5:1. Patients in the 20-39 age group accounted for about 78
percent of the total, according to Ministry of Health statistics.
</P>
<P>
However, AIDS experts estimated that China had 150,000 to
200,000 persons testing HIV positive by the end of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, they warned that any failure to promptly adopt
effective measures could possibly increase the number to one
million by the year 2000 and as many as 10 million by the year
2010.
</P>
<P>
"The multiple use of needles and the growth of prostitution have
emerged as two major risks raising the possibility of an outbrake
of HIV/AIDS in China," they acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
"We will work hard to control epidemic level at under 1.5
million cases during the next 12 years," said Wang Zhao, director
of the MOH Disease Control Department.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980109.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Publishes HIV/AIDS Figures   (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
She noted that China will strive to improve its national
HIV/AIDS prevention and control network which is under leadership
of the central government in cooperation with governmental
departments and people from all sectors of society.
</P>
<P>
"We must halt HIV transmissions through blood transfusions by
2000, while at the same time curbing drug abuse and controlling
the annual growth rate of sexually transmitted diseases (STDs) at
a level below 15 percent," according to Wang.
</P>
<P>
The goals are explicitly defined in medium- and long-term Plans
for AIDS and STD control in China (1997-2010). The plans were
jointly drafted by the State Planning Commission, the State
Science and Technology Commission, the Ministry of Finance and the
Ministry of Health.
</P>
<P>
"The plans will be implemented following approval by the State
Council," said Wang.  
</P>
