<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam's Foreign Trade Deficit Down 41 Percent in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam's foreign trade deficit
was 2.3 billion U.S. dollars in 1997, down 41 percent from 1996,
Vietnam News Agency (VNA) reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Exports amounted to 8.905 billion dollars, a 22.7 percent rise
from 1996, while imports totalled 11.25 billion dollars, 1 percent
up, the Ministry of Trade was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Of the exports, 6.4 billion dollars were equally divided between
the light industry and small handicraft, up 54.8 percent; and
agriculture, forestry and sea products, up 6.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The exports of heavy industry products and minerals totalled
2.3 billion dollars, 13.5 percent up from 1996.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's major exports included coffee, tea, cashews, rice and
footwear.
</P>
<P>
Materials and fuel accounted for the biggest part of the
imports with 7.1 billion dollars, followed by machinery and
accessories, 3.1 billion dollars; and consumer goods, 1 billion
dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
