<HEADLINE> Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President Soeharto on
Friday met with three ministers, a military official and an
economic advisor, and is aware of rumors of a coup d'etat at the
Presidential Palace, a senior official said.
</P>
<P>
"The president received his guests from 8:00 a.m. to 11:00 a.m.
and gave instructions to his ministers," the official Antara News
Agency quoted Minister/State Secretary Moerdiono as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said the president was aware rumors that he was very ill
were circulating.
</P>
<P>
"Those reports are groundless," Moerdiono said. He also denied
that the head of state along with his family had left the country.
</P>
<P>
On suggestions by several parties to hold a national dialogue
on ways to overcome the current monetary crisis, Moerdiono said
the crisis could not be overcome merely with a national dialogue.
</P>
<P>
More concrete measures would be needed, he said.
</P>
<P>
The monetary crisis, which started early July last year in
Southeast Asia, has brought great losses to Indonesia's economy.
The country's currency, the rupiah, has declined by about 300
percent against the U.S. dollar since last July.
</P>
<P>
The crisis has also caused Indonesia's economic growth rate to
fall from 7.98 percent in 1996 to 5.1 percent in 1997. The
country's inflation rate rose to 11.5 percent last year from 6.47
percent in 1996.  
</P>
</TEXT>
