<HEADLINE> Election Campaign Caravan of Extreme-Right Blocked </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 9 (Xinhua) -- The French police Friday blocked
an election campaign caravan of the extreme-right National Front
(FN) in the central seventh district of Paris.
</P>
<P>
Agence France-Presse (AFP) reported the caravan, consisting of
six vehicles covered with posters, were prepared to go around town
in a campaign for the regional elections scheduled for March.
</P>
<P>
The police stopped the caravan from moving ahead because it
would cause traffic jams and the FN had not applied for
permission, said AFP.
</P>
<P>
However, Jean-Yves Le Gallou, the FN candidate for presidency
of the regional council, or local parliament, of the Paris region,
said police officers told him the caravan was stopped because of
its posters.
</P>
<P>
The FN candidates for the deputies of the regional council
meeting at a location nearby immediately denounced the police
action as "an attack on democracy and freedom of expression."
</P>
</TEXT>
