<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Ambassador Calls for Expanded Educational Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 9 (Xinhua) -- British Ambassador to China
Leonard Appleyard said today that he looks forward to expanded
educational cooperation between Britain and China in the
next century.
</P>
<P>
In a message to the '98 British Education Exhibition, which
was opened here today, Appleyard said cooperation is expanding
in the educational field of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He said that the cooperation, which has extended from
standard academic areas to business and industrial training, has
helped promote commercial and technical development between the
two nations.
</P>
<P>
Related efforts will enhance the skills and expertise required
for the future prosperity of the two countries, said Appleyard.
</P>
<P>
The three-day exhibition will present Britain's academic
achievements to the Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition, the largest of its kind held in China in recent
years, is expected to promote understanding between the two sides,
according to the State Education Commission of China.
</P>
<P>
Britain is considered to be a worldwide pioneer of modern
education and has an excellent reputation for cultivating
outstanding students. The country, which has a somewhat rigid but
straightforward educational style, is in the process of reform to
transform the sector.
</P>
<P>
Over the past decade, China has paid great attenion to the
educational sector and introduced reform measures in the
institutions of higher learning.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition is being sponsored by the China Education
Association for International Exchanges and the British Embassy in
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Wan Guoquan, vice-chairman of the National Committee of the
Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference, attended the
opening ceremony of the exhibition along with Appleyard. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
