<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N. Ireland Minister Meet Maze Prisoners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Northern Ireland Secretary Mo
Mowlam arrived Friday at Maze Prison near Belfast for a meeting
with loyalist inmates on inter-party peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Mowlam were meeting the pro-British loyalist extremists in the
prison to back a drive for peace flagging under recent violence in
the divided province, reports arriving here said.
</P>
<P>
She caused a shock on Wednesday while announcing her plan to
meet the prisoners, who are called loyalists because they support
the British rule of Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
Prisoners are held in awesome respect by the leaders of the
underground forces and have a key influence on decisions about
truces and political strategy.
</P>
<P>
The move is seen as a gamble aimed at getting 120 loyalist
extremists to renew their backing for peace talks and bolster a
three-year loyalist truce.
</P>
<P>
Tension has been high in Northern Ireland since Christmas, when
a loyalist paramilitary group leader, Billy Wright, was gunned
down at Maze by members of the Irish National Liberation Army
(INLA), a Catholic republican splinter group.
</P>
<P>
Wright's followers then killed two Catholics and wounded
several more in Northern Ireland for revenge.
</P>
<P>
Mowlam will also hold separate meetings with Irish Republican
Army (IRA) prisoners later in the day.
</P>
<P>
IRA, an outlawed paramilitary organization against the British
rule, called a ceasefire last July to allow its political wing
Sinn Fein to join the multi-party peace talks on the future of
Northern Ireland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
