<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flights of Foreign Airlines to S. Korea Decrease </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, January 9 (Xinhua) -- The sharp depreciation of the
South Korean won caused by the current financial crisis and
slumping number of Korean travelers have prompted some foreign
airlines to stop or reduce their flights passing through Seoul.
</P>
<P>
Continental Micronesia stopped its weekly seven flights on
Seoul-Guam-Saipan route last December, and Air New Zealand and
Turkish Airlines followed the suit.
</P>
<P>
From the beginning of this year, Air New Zealand stopped
flights on Seoul-Brisbane-Auckland routes while Turkish Airlines,
which launched service to Seoul from Istanbul just two months ago,
stopped its operation on January 2.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Ansett Australia International, which began its
South Korean flights in 1996, decided to suspend its services
between Australia and South Korea in February.
</P>
<P>
Craig Wallace, general manager of Ansett Australia
International, said South Korea's economic crisis shows that its
Korean services are no longer commercially viable.
</P>
<P>
Qantas Airways, another Australian airline which has so far
scheduled four flights a week to South Korea, has announced
recently that it would stop its current operations between
Australia and Seoul as from February 1.
</P>
<P>
More airlines from Southeast Asian countries, analysts said,
are expected to reduce their flights to South Korea sooner or
later as Thai Airways reportedly plans to reduce by four flights a
week between Seoul and Bangkok; and Malaysia Airlines intends to
cut the flights to three a week from five. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
