<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Customs Departments Recovering Lost Duty Revenue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Chinese customs departments
recovered 1.5 billion yuan (180 million US dollars) worth duties
which smugglers and exporters evaded during 1997, according to the
General Administration of Customs.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the administration launched nationwide drive to check
the smuggling of rolled steel, steel plates, copper and edible oil
products.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of last year alone, local customs offices
looked into 22 cases involving copper smuggling and recovered
duties in the neighborhood of 200 million yuan. In the latter half
of the year, the said offices handled 12 cases involving over
60,000 tons of smuggled edible oil valued at 100 million yuan (12
million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Customs offices across the country examined and investigated
more than 14,200 companies during 1997, with the discovery of
1,446 smuggling cases and the recovery 1.5 billion yuan. Companies
and individuals involved in evading the payment of duties paid
fines totalling 51 million yuan (6.1 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
In 1994, the administration implemented a supervision system to
check on the imports and exports of local enterprises. 
</P>
</TEXT>
