<HEADLINE> Chinese Computer Giant Eyes International Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Beijing University's Founder
Group Corp., one of China's major manufacturers of computer
hardware and software, plans to make bigger strides in the world
market during 1998, according to Founder President Wang Xuan.
</P>
<P>
The company scored notable success in exploring foreign
markets in 1997, with its product line, including printing
software and monitors selling well overseas.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the Founder Group sold software valued at three
million US dollars to Japanese printing firms, with its graphics
processors entering markets in Hong Kong, Taiwan, Malaysia and
Japan.
</P>
<P>
Some 60 percent of two million monitors manufactured last year
were exported to foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a Friday news conference, Wang said the company's
ambitious 1998 plan is to export its graphic processors to North
America.
</P>
<P>
"Our company is a newcomer, but our products are nonetheless
competitive on the international market in terms of performance
and quality," said Wang.
</P>
<P>
The company achieved a 1997 sales volume of close to six
billion yuan (723 million US dollars), up 50 percent on the
previous year, he said, adding that the company earmarks some 4-5
percent of its annual earnings for new product development.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980109.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korean Government Urged to Avoid Further Credit Crunch </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, January 9 (Xinhua) -- A private institute Friday called
for renegotiations with the International Monetary Fund (IMF) to
extend the deadline of South Korean banks' capital adequacy ratio,
so as to avoid further credit crunch.
</P>
<P>
The government, said Korea Institute for Industrial Economics
and Trade, should take measures to boost the financial status of
domestic banks so as to meet capital adequacy ratio of 8 percent,
as required by the Banks for International Settlements (BIS).
</P>
<P>
These measures, the institute said in a report, could include
preference shares, increase of credit guarantee funds and
re-arrangement of bad loans.
</P>
<P>
Domestic banks' refusal to make fresh loans while demanding
payment on the existing loans to maintain capital ratio will put a
serious squeeze on credit, said the report.
</P>
<P>
It could lead to sharp interest rate hikes, a paralysis in
export and import and a decline in growth rate, it added.
</P>
<P>
"Even the industrialized nations, such as the United States and
Japan, experienced such a crisis since the system of BIS-required
ratio was adopted at the meeting of central bank presidents of
group of seven (G-7) industrialized nations in 1987," it said.
</P>
<P>
Many countries, however, could be able to overcome such a
crisis by extending the period for calculating the BIS ratio,
pouring more public funds and increasing support for small- and
medium-size companies, the institute said.
</P>
<P>
President-elect Kim Dae-jung has promised to implement the
agreement signed with the IMF last December for a loan of 57
billion U.S. dollars to rescue the country from the current
financial crisis caused by the failure of conglomerates and bad
loans of financial institutions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
