<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Rules Out Devaluation of Rupee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, January 9 (Xinhua)-- Indian Finance Minister P.
Chidambaram Friday ruled out any competitive devaluation of the
country's currency rupee to make good the loss arising from steep
falls in the values of East and Southeast Asian currencies.
</P>
<P>
"If you want competitive devaluation, I am ruling it out,"
Chidambaram told a special plenary session of the fourth
partnership summit, which opened Thursday in Chennai, southern
India.
</P>
<P>
Admitting that Indian exports had been hit by the Asian
currency tumbledown, he said the route to recovery was by
improving quality, reliability and delivery, and not merely by
devaluing the currency.
</P>
<P>
Pointing out that Asian currencies were expected to firm up by
the end of 1998, he said Indian exports would recover then.
</P>
<P>
Imports from the Asian tiger economies have become cheaper in
the international market compared to imports from India, prompting
Indian exporters to call for competitive devaluation of rupee.
Indian exports have been hit hard by the currency crisis in
Southeast Asia, particularly in gems and jewelry, textiles and
leather sectors.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
