<DOCNO> XIE19980109.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cypriot FM Heads for Greece on Cyprus Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus Foreign Minister Ioannis
Kasoulides left for Athens today for talks with Greek Foreign
Ministry officials on the latest developments in the region.
</P>
<P>
Before his departure, Kasoulides said he will hold talks with
Greek Foreign Minister Theodoros Pangalos and other officials to
review developments in the Cyprus problem, in the wake of the
Luxembourg European Council summit last month.
</P>
<P>
The European Union (EU) leaders confirmed they had decided to
begin membership talks with Cyprus on March 30, 1998.
</P>
<P>
Kasoulides described the current period as "critical" because
of the situation in the Aegean Sea and the Turkish provocations
with repeated violations of Greece's air space and Athens Flight
Information Region by Turkish jet fighters.
</P>
<P>
Kasoulides said any developments would have consequences on
Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkish troops
landed and took over the northern third of the island following of
a short-lived Greek Cypriot coup seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
Greece and Turkey, both NATO allies, have long been at odds
with each other over Cyprus, a strategic island in east
Mediterranean.
</P>
<P>
After his Athens talks, Kasoulides is expected to fly to
Lisbon for talks with his Portuguese counterpart, concentrating on
issues relating to Cyprus' bid to become a full member of the EU.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
