<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Materials on 2,500-Year-Old Great Wall Found </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Five elderly people in east
China's Shandong Province have collected the most complete
materials to date on the 2,500-year-old Qi Great Wall after an
investigation tour.
</P>
<P>
The great wall, a section in Shandong built by the Qi State
during the Warring States period (475-221 B.C.), was more than 470
years older than that built in the Qin Dynasty (221-207 B.C.). It
is regarded as the "father of the Great Wall" by historians.
</P>
<P>
The 367-day investigation on foot has for the first time
measured the accurate length of the Qi Great Wall, which is 618.9
km. Also found this time was a large number of legends and folk
songs, and many materials on the great wall section including word
records, pictures and atlas.
</P>
<P>
They are very helpful to the research of the military, politics
and culture of the Warring States period, experts say. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980109.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwanda to Rehabilitate Judicial System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIGALI, January 9 (Xinhua) -- The Rwandan government has
decided to rehabilitate its judicial system which was severely
damaged by the 1994 genocide, with financial support from the
U.S. government.
</P>
<P>
Rwandan Minister of Justice Faustin Nteziryayo today met U.S.
Ambassador to Rwanda Robert Gribbin on projects supported by his
government in this regard.
</P>
<P>
"These projects include training the judicial staff, providing
equipment and repairing court houses," state-run Radio Rwanda
announced.
</P>
<P>
Both the Minister and the US Ambassador examined the cases of
genocide suspects at large outside the country, and reiterated
the responsibility of nations to extradite them to the
International Crimes Tribunal in Arusha, in northern Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Three years after the genocide, a lot has been done in
rehabilitating the ravaged judicial system notably in training
new magistrates, investigators, and prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
However, officials in the ministry of justice indicate that
many more are needed to overcome the serious challenge of trying
over 120,000 genocide suspects currently detained in Rwanda
prisons.
</P>
<P>
During her last visit to Rwanda in December 1997, U.S.
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright declared that the U.S. will
pledge a 30-million-dollar-package in the framework of the
justice initiative aimed at developing "impartial, credible, and
effective" justice systems. 
</P>
