<DOCNO> XIE19980109.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-09 12:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Air Base Ready Later This Month </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, January 9 (Xinhua) -- The Air Force Base near the
western coastal town of Paphos, Cyprus, will be ready for use
later this month, President Glafcos Clerides has announced.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with a local television program Thursday night,
President Clerides said in conjunction with the installation of
the Russian S-300 surface-to-air missiles, the island's air space
would be fully covered.
</P>
<P>
That would provide "persuasive air coverage against enemy
jets," he said.
</P>
<P>
The air force base was constructed under a joint defense pact,
signed in 1993 between Cypriot and Greek governments. Under the
pact, Greece will provide military assistance if Cyprus is
attacked.
</P>
<P>
To raise its defense capability, the Cypriot government also
decided last year to buy Russian-made anti-aircraft S-300
missiles, which will be delivered this summer.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot government has decided to deploy those advanced
missiles later this year despite threats from Turkey to launch a
pre-emptive strike if it does.
</P>
<P>
Clerides said the main reason for boosting Cypriot air defenses
is to protect vulnerable tanks on the ground.
</P>
<P>
"The S-300 missiles will cause such damage to the enemy's air
force that they will think twice before attacking again," he added.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the island in the wake
of a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
