<HEADLINE> India's Reform Process Will Continue: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Indian Union Industry Minister
M. Maran said Friday that his country's reform process would
continue as it is irreversible.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the Fourth Partnership Summit, which opened Thursday
in Chennai, capital of Tamil Nadu, southern India, Maran said the
various states in the country would become the driving force of
the reforms and they would not allow the central government to
soft-pedal the reform process already initiated. "Our agenda is to
ensure that India becomes the third largest economy in the world."
</P>
<P>
Stressing the need for encouraging foreign investment, Maran
said such investment is essential because it brings in modern
technology and better management practices and obtains new markets
for the country, besides creating more jobs.
</P>
<P>
"We want more gain than pain and we want more support and not
criticism of the reform," he said.  
