<HEADLINE> Share Prices Plummet on Singapore Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Share prices plummeted again
for the fifth running day on the Singapore market Friday after
hitting a record low in seven years Thursday, with the benchmark
Straits Times Industrials Index (STII) losing 94.35 points to
close at 1,176.35.
</P>
<P>
The total market volume increased to 340.8 million units,
valued at 720.32 million Singapore dollars (about 406.96 million
U.S. dollars). Declines overwhelmed advances by 308 to 60 while
244 other counters remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
UPP was the most actively traded counter as it registered a
turnover of 21.69 million units. It was followed by DBS
(Development Bank of Singapore) Land which had 19.04 million
shares traded. Asian Food and Property was next with 17.42 million
shares changed hands.
</P>
<P>
Venture led the gainers of the day as it rose by 30 cents to
finish at 4.1 Singapore dollars. Elec picked up by 28 cents to end
at 4.3 U.S. dollars while Keppel FELS increased by 22 cents to
close at 4 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, local computer sound card maker Creative 50
was the biggest loser as it declined by 1.8 dollars to end at 28.9
Singapore dollars. DBS Foreign fell by 1.3 dollars to close at
10.6 Singapore dollars while Cycle &AMP; Carriage lost 1.22 dollars to
finish at 4.68 Singapore dollars and OCBC (Overseas Chinese
Banking Corporation) Foreign was one dollar lower at 6.5 Singapore
dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
