<HEADLINE> Good Health Rated First in Survey of Chinese Citizens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 9 (Xinhua) -- To have excellent health was the
first choice of most Chinese citizens for the second consecutive
year, according to a survey carried out among 5,130 urban families
in 10 major Chinese cities.
</P>
<P>
The survey, done by Beijing-based Horizon Market Survey and
Analysis Company at the end of 1997, says that 30 percent of the
respondents said their first wish for 1998 is good health.
</P>
<P>
The second choice of respondents, 20 percent, was making more
money and investing in stocks, stamps and bonds.
</P>
<P>
Coming in third, with 9.6 percent, was the desire to do a good
job in 1998, while 8.9 percent said they hope that their children
find a good job or a good school, says the survey results carried
in the "Beijing Economic Daily."
</P>
<P>
Though not listed as their first choice, 80 percent of the
respondents said they hope to buy an apartment in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Good health was also the first choice of most Chinese citizens
in 1997, and 34.7 percent of the respondents are satisfied with
what they did and achieved in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
