<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> External Investment Flows Into HK Manufacturing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 9 (Xinhua) -- External investment has flowed
steadily into Hong Kong's manufacturing industries, as shown in a
government survey released here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Inward direct investment in the manufacturing sector reached 48
billion HK dollars (6.15 billion U.S. dollars) at the end of 1996,
a 6-percent rise over the previous year, according to the latest
annual survey, conducted by the Industry Department.
</P>
<P>
The total number of companies with external investment was 403
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
External investment in manufacturing industries grew by 10
percent on average each year between 1994 and 1996, the survey
found.
</P>
<P>
"The steady increase reflects the attractiveness of Hong Kong
as a manufacturing base," said Francis Ho, director-general of
industry, at a briefing Friday.
</P>
<P>
Japan continued to be the leading source country of external
investment in Hong Kong's manufacturing sector, contributing 38
percent to the total inflow of capital. The United States ranked
second, followed by Britain and the Chinese mainland.
</P>
<P>
The external investment mainly went to four industries, namely,
 electronics, electrical products, chemicals and food and
beverages, which together accounted for almost 60 percent of the
total.
</P>
<P>
Ho said: "About 75 percent of the respondents in the survey
consider that Hong Kong's overall manufacturing investment
environment has been improved or remains more or less the same."
</P>
<P>
Infrastructure, banking and financial facilities and labor
productivity were regarded as the most important and favorable
factors in Hong Kong while cost of doing business, namely high
wages and rents, was considered as unfavorable, according to the
survey.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
