<DOCNO> XIE19980109.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sierra Leone Shows Concern over Vehicle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, January 9 (Xinhua) -- The military government in
Sierra Leone today expressed concern over what it described as
"sustained harassment and inhuman treatment" regarding the
detention of vehicles and citizens by Nigerian troop in ECOMOG at
the Jui Checkpoint, 13 miles east of the capital.
</P>
<P>
According to state radio, a statement released from the
Department of Information has appealed to the international
community and the Economic Community of West African States
(ECOWAS) "to urge Nigeria to stop this complete affront to the
U.N. Security Council Resolution 1132."
</P>
<P>
The release called on the Nigerians " to stop this act
immediately as it goes against the Conakry Peace Plan" signed in
October last year.
</P>
<P>
It reminded the Nigerians that "Sierra Leone is a nation whose
territorial integrity should be respected."
</P>
<P>
Over 15 trucks, some with Guinean registration plates, are
still detained at the Checkpoint by the Nigerians after they were
impounded nearly a week ago.
</P>
<P>
The trucks, including a state-owned National Petroleum tanker
with 1,800 gallons of diesel, were heading either for the
interior or neighbouring Guinea.
</P>
<P>
A Nigerian Captain reached by telephone at the Checkpoint
explained that the trucks were impounded as there were evidence
that their goods, including cocoa and coffee were being taken to
Guinea for shipment overseas.
</P>
<P>
"When we inspected the trucks, we found papers signed by the
inspector-general of police for the vehicles to go through
checkpoints manned by Sierra Leone soldiers and documents from
Sierra Leone Trade officials giving clearance for the goods to be
shipped overseas.
</P>
<P>
"Obviously, these violate the sanction and embargo now in
force in the country," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
