<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Insures One Third of Government, Institution Employees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 9 (Xinhua) -- One third of government and
social institution employees in China, with a population of 11.32
million, have joined in various social insurance schemes, the
Ministry of Personnel announced here today.
</P>
<P>
To date, more than 1,700 prefectures, cities and counties in
28 provinces across the country have introduced social insurance
for workers in local government and social institutions, the
Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Among them, more than 680 prefectures, cities and counties have
provided pension insurance for all employees of local governments
and institutions, more than 300 have begun to offer unemployment
insurance, and many more are now trying to introduce job-related
accident insurance.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the Ministry of Personnel show that by the
first half of 1997 social insurance funds for government and
institution employees across the country totaled 7.8 billion yuan
(950 million U.S. dollars), 6.9 billion more than in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The majority of the funds came from central and local
government budgets, a Ministry official revealed.
</P>
<P>
The 15th National Congress of the Communist Party of China
(CPC), convened in Beijing in September, called for the founding
of a social security system based on the social insurance and
poverty-relief scheme.
</P>
<P>
"The introduction of the social insurance scheme in governments
and social institutions is a major component of, and support for,
China's personnel system reform," said Song Defu, minister of
personnel.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that 19 provinces, municipalities and
autonomous regions -- including Sichuan, Guizhou, Shaanxi and
Chongqing -- have worked out their own plans to insure employees
of local governments and social institutions.
</P>
<P>
According to sources available, the number of people in
governments and social institutions across the country exclusively
assigned to work on the insurance scheme has now exceeds 8,000,
and many of them are equipped with computerized facilities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
