<HEADLINE> Chinese Swimming Team Issues Statement on Drugs Controversy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PERTH, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Following is the statement issued
by the Chinese swimming team here Friday night:
</P>
<P>
"On January 8, 1998, part of the Chinese swimming team had a
stopover in Sydney on their way to Perth for the Eighth World
Swimming Championships. In a routine baggage check at the Sydney
Airport, one of the swimmers Yuan Yuan was believed to have in her
baggage suspicious substance banned by the Sydney Customs.
</P>
<P>
"Upon arrival of the above-mentioned group of people in Perth,
the Chinese Swimming Delegation made inquires of the people
concerned in regards to what had happened.
</P>
<P>
"According to swimming coach, Mr. Zhou Zhewen, before they came
here someone asked him to take the substance over here. At the
Sydney Customs, the customs officials inquired these two people
and Mr. Zhou made an explanation. As this is their individual
behavior they will be responsible for all the consequences thus
arising.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese Swimming Delegation holds that carrying things for
other people on the way to the World Swimming Championships
violates the delegation's disciplines and was definitely wrong.
Once the Australian Customs officially confirms that it is a
banned drug, the Chinese Swimming Delegation shall deprive these
two people of the right to participate in the current world
championships. Further action will then be taken in accordance
with the rules and regulations of the Chinese Swimming
Association, and the FINA will be duly informed of the result.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese Swimming Association has always been fighting
against any doping practice and insisting on the 'Three Strict'
Anti-doping Policy, namely, 'strict prohibition, strict
examination and strict sanction.' However, we are strongly against
that this individual behavior being regarded as a collective
action.
</P>
<P>
"Holding high the banner of fighting against doping, the
Chinese Swimming Association is willing to co-operate with the
other sports federations and make unremitting efforts to ensure
the successful fight against doping and safeguard the purity of
the Olympic Movement." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
