<HEADLINE> HK Attractive as Regional Headquarters Location </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong remains an
attractive base for overseas companies to build their regional
operations, according to a government survey released here
Friday.
</P>
<P>
By June 1, 1997, overseas companies had set up 2,530 regional
operations in Hong Kong, a 10-percent rise from a year before,
said the annual survey conducted by the Industry Department.
</P>
<P>
These regional operations include 924 regional headquarters and
1,606 regional offices and nearly half of them built up their
presence in Hong Kong in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
Francis Ho, director-general of industry, said at a news
briefing Friday: "The survey reaffirmed the increasing importance
of Hong Kong as a major regional business center for overseas
companies."
</P>
<P>
Ninety-one percent of the respondents said the attractiveness
of Hong Kong as a location for regional headquarters or regional
office has improved or remains the same, the survey found.
</P>
<P>
Considered as the most important and favorable factors are
banking and financial facilities, government economic policy,
infrastructure, rule of law, tax regime, transparent government
and access to information.
</P>
<P>
The survey showed that the United States, with 219 companies,
has the largest number of regional headquarters in Hong Kong,
followed by Japan, the Chinese mainland and Britain. In terms of
the number of regional offices, Japan tops the list with 378
companies and the United States comes second with 262.  
</P>
</TEXT>
