<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-U.S. Zoologists Find Tibetan Antelope's Breeding Site </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, January 9 (Xinhua)--A Sino-U.S. wildlife exploration
team has located the breeding place of the Tibetan antelope,
solving a riddle that has puzzled zoologists worldwide for nearly
200 years.
</P>
<P>
The team discovered last summer that Tibetan antelope, a rare
species roaming only in the northernmost part of the Tibet
Autonomous Region, would give birth to their babies mainly at the
foot of the southern slope of the Kunlun Mountains and along the
banks of Hoh Xil Lake -- both 5,000 meters above sea level.
</P>
<P>
The team was headed by Liu Wulin, a wildlife conservationist
with the Tibet Autonomous Region's Forestry Bureau, and George
Schallei of the Wildlife Conservation Society of the United States.
</P>
<P>
With long, straight horns and coated with thick hair, Tibetan
antelopes are so fast that they can outrun wolves. They live in
the southern part of Changtang Prairie in winter.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the season when female antelopes are to give birth to
their babies, they travel north with male antelopes in large
numbers.
</P>
<P>
But male antelopes halt in the middle of the prairie while the
females continue their trip. They then return with baby antelopes
and rejoin the large group for the trip back south.
</P>
<P>
Scientists and zoologists from more than 20 countries and
regions around the world had come to Tibet since the 19th century
trying to find out the antelopes' travel route and breeding place,
but to no avail.
</P>
<P>
The Sino-U.S. team's previous attempts also had failed. Big
mountains, rivers and waterfalls on the journey often eradicated
any trace of the traveling antelopes.
</P>
<P>
"We have seen the baby antelopes," said Liu Wulin. "Born only
three to five days, they run as fast as rabbits."
</P>
<P>
The team concludes that Tibetan antelopes choose the northern
region as their breeding place because the thick-haired animal
wants a cool place to give birth in summer, plus the northern
prairie has rich freshwater ponds and lush grasses.
</P>
<P>
Liu said the discovery is significant as zoologists now can
better protect the rare animal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980109.0157 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Soeharto, Clinton Discuss Currency Crisis on Phone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 9 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
talked with Indonesian President Soeharto on the phone Friday
morning about Indonesia's economic situation, a cabinet minister
said.
</P>
<P>
Minister/State Secretary Moerdiono told reporters that Clinton
expressed his concern about the situation in Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
"President Clinton is apprehensive about the economic and
currency crisis which is affecting Indonesia," he said.
</P>
<P>
In their 25-minute conversation, Clinton expressed the belief
that Indonesia will overcome its crisis because its restructuring
and reform programs are backed by the International Monetary Fund
(IMF).
</P>
<P>
"President Clinton supports implementing the programs and will
send U.S. Deputy Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers to Indonesia
to hold discussions with President Soeharto and other top
officials," Moerdiono said.
</P>
<P>
"Indonesia, with a grateful heart, will accept the U.S.
government's special envoy," Moerdiono said, adding that Summers'
visit aims to obtain first-hand information about Indonesia's
policies for handling the ongoing monetary crisis.
</P>
<P>
After the telephone conversation, Soeharto met with Minister of
Trade and Industry Tunky Ariwibowo and economic advisor Widjojo
Nitisastro, whom the president asked to seriously examine the
IMF-supported restructuring program.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian rupiah, the country's currency, hit a record low
of 11,000 against the U.S. dollar in late trading Thursday. The
rupiah has declined by about 300 percent since early July last
year.
</P>
<P>
Local dealers attributed the sharp drop of the rupiah to the
worsening public confidence in the country's economy and the IMF's
disappointment over the Indonesian government's programs in coping
with the monetary crisis.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia, which agreed to an IMF-led bailout of more than 30
billion U.S. dollars in October last year, has committed to
conducting a series of reforms, including those in the financial,
fiscal and banking sectors.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian government closed 16 insolvent private banks in
early November as part of its reform package. In December the
government announced a plan to merge a number of state-run banks
before July 31, 1998.
</P>
<P>
However, IMF officials on Tuesday called Indonesia's economic
crisis worrisome and faulted the Jakarta government's effort to
follow through on pledges to restructure the nation's economy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
