<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Soars on Central Bank Action </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 9 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar went up
by one U.S. cent in less than an hour Friday as the Reserve Bank
of Australia (RBA) intervened in the foreign exchange market for
the first time since 1993.
</P>
<P>
The RBA's move to buy Australian dollars and sell the greenback
pushed the local currency up from an 11-year low of 63.18 U.S.
cents and sent it bursting through the 64-U.S. cent level.
</P>
<P>
By the close of the local session, the currency had retreated
slightly to 63.98 U.S. cents, lower than the levels reached at the
height of the RBA-inspired rally, but still well above the 63.28
U.S. cents at the opening and 63.68 U.S. cents Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The rally was just in time to prevent the unit falling through
the critical support level of 63 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
Many market analysts had predicted that a break below that
level would have hastened the currency's downward spiral.
</P>
<P>
The Australian currency has been steadily heading lower since
March 1997 when it peaked at around 80 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
It ended Friday at 84.27 Japanese yen, from 84.39 Thursday and
at 1.1608 marks, from 1.1621.  
</P>
</TEXT>
