<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Host Int'l Investment Forum in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 9 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government has
concluded plans to organize an international investors forum the
coming June and open investment promotion offices in some Asian
countries.
</P>
<P>
The countries will include Japan, China, Malaysia and some
others in southeast Asia, according to Industry Minister Onikepo
Akande.
</P>
<P>
The measure aimed at attracting foreign investment will
expectedly boost the country's privatization efforts, the
minister said when presenting the ministry's budget in the
capital Abuja Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The decision in this respect "is in consonance with our
resolve to attract needed foreign capital, machinery and
equipment which, though very necessary, are not locally
available," she said.
</P>
<P>
"Negotiations leading to the signing of investment promotion
and protection agreements with interested countries would
continue in 1998," the minister said, quoted by today's This Day
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
According to her, efforts to implement this year's budget will
be made "to step up our investment promotion initiative
particularly now that the governing council of the Nigerian
Investment Promotion Commission has been inaugurated while its
activities commenced in earnest".
</P>
<P>
The first priority of her ministry has been and will continue
to be on small and medium-sized enterprise promotion and
development to hold the upliftment of the industrial sector of
the country, the minister noted.
</P>
<P>
Certain key sub-sectors in the ministry, including those of
machine tools, sugar, pulp and paper and cement, will receive a
boost from the 1998 budget, she added.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, Nigeria's sugar industry can only
meet about 10 percent of the domestic requirement estimated at
one million tons a year.
</P>
<P>
To reverse this, the minister said the government is to "aim
to achieve at least 70 percent self-sufficiency in sugar
production by the turn of the century". 
</P>
</TEXT>
