<HEADLINE> Assembly Plant for German Fighters in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Germany's Daimler-Benz
Aerospace has confirmed that it was in talks with South Africa to
set up a local assembly plant for its jet fighters, The Star
daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
Germany is believed to have made the South African National
Defense Force's short-list of products and suppliers for an arms
purchase of 10 billion Rand (2.04 billion U.S. Dollars) approved
by South African parliament in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Michael Woerfel, president of Daimler-Benz's southern African
branch, said Thursday that the final assembly of the company's
advanced jet trainers and more than 50 percent of the work and
development, integration and supply of the mission systems for
the aircraft would be undertaken in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
He said that with predicted sales of between 700 and 800 units
by 2025, the deal could earn South Africa several billion Rand
over a 25-30 years period.
</P>
<P>
The advanced jet trainers have already been presented to
potential customers. Two countries with a total procurement
volume of 250 aircraft have short-listed the trainers, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
While the agreement is still being negotiated with South
Africa's arms manufacturer Denel, the German group expects first
deliveries from 2005.
</P>
<P>
Daimler-Benz is also negotiating similar cooperation with
South Korea's Hyundai Space. 
</P>
