<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Road Death Toll Expected to Be Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 9 (Xinhua) -- The road death toll since
December 1 last year is expected to be lower as compared with the
authorities said.
</P>
<P>
They said in a statement Thursday that 844 people had died in
traffic accidents since December 1 last year. In comparison,
1,242 people died on South Afircan roads between December 3, 1996
and January 12, 1997.
</P>
<P>
"This is a definte indication that motorists heeded our
warnings and generally cooperated with the traffic authorities in
their attempts to reduce the carnage on our roads," said Leonard
Ramatlakane, a senior official in the Transport Department.
</P>
<P>
"It is also, I am sure, the consequence of the intensified
law enforcement effort during (last) December, when no less than
24,078 drivers were charged with over-speeding, and 254 with
drinking and driving offences," Ramatlakane said.
</P>
<P>
According to the Transport Department, since October 1 last
year#,which saw a government-sponsored Arrive Alive campaign,
11,845 drivers and passengers were charged with failing to wear
seat belts.
</P>
<P>
The fatalities so far included 369 passengers, 273
pedestrians and 202 drivers, the department said.
</P>
<P>
Traffic volumes were expected to increase considerably today,
peaking on Sunday, when holiday-makers returned for the school
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
