<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Decline on Asia, U.S. Stock Falls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 9 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market
declined by about 2 percent Friday as falls across international
markets shook local investor confidence.
</P>
<P>
Australian stocks with the greatest exposure to Asia were dealt
the hardest blow because of growing concerns about the prospects
of Southeast Asia's financial markets and the impact on local
companies' earnings.
</P>
<P>
The All Ordinaries Index fell 47.6 points or 1.8 percent to
2603.1, having earlier dipped to as low as 2585.8.
</P>
<P>
On Wall Street overnight, the Dow Jones industrial average
plunged 99.65 points to 7802.62 on the back of Asian market losses
and concerns that the International Monetary Fund's prescriptions
for Asian countries were being ignored.
</P>
<P>
"The latest events in Asia and Wall Street obviously got market
players nervous here today," Henderson Charlton Jones broker
Philip Toop said. "Those stocks with strong links to the region
suffered the most. People will be watching New York closely
tonight for a lead on Monday."
</P>
<P>
The All Resources Index shed 27.3 points or 2.5 percent to
1084.3 while the Industrials Index slipped 74.3 points to 4500.2.
</P>
<P>
Weaker copper prices saw Rio Tinto drop 54.5 cents, BHP 39
cents, WMC 17 cents and MIM 4 cents.
</P>
<P>
Forty-four cents was wiped from ANZ Bank, which has the
greatest exposure to Asia among the big four banks. It finished at
9.87 Australian dollars while NAB slipped 21 cents, Westpac 18.6
cents and CBA 24 cents.
</P>
<P>
The gold sector closed seven points softer with the index
slipping below the 1000-point barrier to stand at 999.7.
</P>
<P>
Among gold stocks, Plutonic was down 24 cents and Normandy 2
cents. But Acacia bucked the trend by rising 12.3 cents.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 312.8 million shares, valued at 935.55
million Australian dollars (598.75 million U.S. dollars), with
falls outpacing rises 731 to 382.  
</P>
</TEXT>
