<HEADLINE> Manila Adopts Measures to Sustain Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 9 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Trade Department
has adopted a "three-step route" measure to cope with the current
currency turmoil and sustain the country's economic growth, the
Philippine News Agency reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Trade and Industry Secretary Cesar Bautista proposed the
measures in his year-end report to President Fidel Ramos.
</P>
<P>
They include calibrated measures to restore financial
stability, productivity improvement measures in enterprises to
increase competitiveness and innovation especially in technology
and marketing areas.
</P>
<P>
Bautista said these steps would help snap companies out of
their gloom and turn regional threats into opportunities.
</P>
<P>
These confidence-building measures, he said, will also help
ensure that the Ramos administration will bow out with high marks
for helping sustain economic growth in his last semester in
office.
</P>
<P>
Under the Ramos administration, the economy achieved its
"longest, uninterrupted period of growth" for the sixth
consecutive year, from zero growth in 1991 to about 6 percent by
October 1997, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, he admitted, the economic growth is expected to slow
down to 5 percent this year due to uncertainties brought about by
the regional currency crisis.  
</P>
