<DOCNO> XIE19980109.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Sets Guiding Principles For Agriculture In 1998 (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Good or poor agricultural harvests rely heavily on farmers'
initiative, which in turn depends on the Party's rural
policies. So, governments at all levels must be held accountable
to carrying out Party policies, including the household-based
contract responsibility system and policies to lighten farmers'
financial burdens and purchase any amount of grain from farmers at
protective prices.
</P>
<P>
China is experiencing a shift from a self-sufficient farming
sector to a commodity-oriented one and from a traditional farming
sector to a modern one. Therefore, efforts should be made to
improve the agricultural structure to adapt to a market
economy. The farm product processing industry should be developed
and made into a new rural economic growth area, as well as a
pillar industry of China's economy.
</P>
<P>
In restructuring the rural industrial structure, it is
necessary to improve to market analysis and prediction, and
provide timely and accurate market information for farmers.
</P>
<P>
Attention should be focused on cultivating country fairs and
farm produce wholesale markets, and on enlivening distribution.
</P>
<P>
Positive and proper measures should be taken to promote
market-oriented agricultural industrialization, and to foster and
support leading enterprises, which will serve as examples in rural
areas in opening up markets, guiding production, and participating
in sales.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980109.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Opposition May Not Keep Deadline of Sri Lankan Gov't </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's main opposition
party, the United National Party (UNP), said Friday morning that
it would not be intimidated by a government deadline to submit
alternative proposals concerning the government's devolution
package.
</P>
<P>
UNP General Secretary Gamini Atukorale said the work on the
constitution, which contains the devolution package, should not be
done in a hurry. The party has asked six more months for it to
come up with a decision on the new constitution proposed by the
People's Alliance (PA) government.
</P>
<P>
The UNP response followed a government decision to make January
31 the deadline for the party to submit its alternative proposals
on the package, the core of the government's peace initiative.
</P>
<P>
Justice, Constitutional Affairs, Ethnic Affairs and National
Integration Minister G. L. Peiris said Thursday that the
government wants to come to an agreement with the UNP and that is
why it gave the party time to submit its proposals.
</P>
<P>
If the government doesn't receive UNP proposals by the end of
January, it will have to consider an alternative course of action
such as a referendum, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
He stated that once the presidential proclamation is made on a
referendum, the government will conduct it in 30 days.
</P>
<P>
The devolution package promises to grant more autonomy to local
authorities in Eastern and Northern provinces, with a view to
ending the conflict between the majority Sinhalese people and the
minority Tamils.
</P>
<P>
Although the ruling PA government has tried repeatedly to win
UNP support for the package, the latter has turned a deaf ear to
the PA's calls and remained silent on the issue.  
</P>
</TEXT>
