<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Doctor Jailed for Medicare Fraud </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 9 (Xinhua) -- A migrant Australian doctor has
been sentenced to eight years in jail for defrauding Medicare of
almost 1 million Australian dollars (about 650,000 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
John William Kibukamusoke, 65, pleaded guilty in the Canberra
Supreme Court on December 17 to 414 charges, committed between
1992 and 1996, and has been in custody since, the Australian
Associated Press reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Kibukamusoke, a former Ugandan high commissioner to Australia,
worked as a general practitioner and kidney specialist in Canberra
from 1982, and at the time of his arrest was also practicing in
two states in Australia. He ran a practice in Bega on the south
coast of New South Wales state in eastern Australia between 1985
and 1991.
</P>
<P>
Most of the 814 patients for whom Kibukamusoke allegedly made
false claims with forged signatures were former Bega patients,
some of whom had died.
</P>
<P>
The Health Insurance Commission found that he had lodged 15,443
bulk billing claims, or 55 percent of all his claims in four
years, for patients he did not see or procedures not performed, or
claimed a higher referral rate when there was no referral from a
general practitioner.
</P>
<P>
Kibukamusoke had lost substantial amounts of money from failed
business ventures.
</P>
<P>
Justice John Gallop said Kibukamusoke had a distinguished
career as a specialist doctor and as a diplomat for Uganda, which
he fled in 1973.
</P>
<P>
"To defraud the Commonwealth of almost 1 million Australian
dollars over a period of four years with a multiplicity of claims
is about as serious as one can imagine," he said.
</P>
<P>
He gave Kibukamusoke a jail term of eight years with a
non-parole period of four years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980109.0175 </DOCNO>
