<HEADLINE> S. Africa Invests Millions to Relieve Rural </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 9 (Xinhua) -- The South African
government has approved 85 million Rand (17.3 million U.S.
Dollars) to create about 17,000 jobs in rural areas as part of
its rural poverty relief program, The Star newspaper said today.
</P>
<P>
Public Works Minister Jeff Radebe announced Thursday that the
projects to be started on January 29, would create about 12,800
temporary and 3,840 permanent jobs.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that women would comprise at least two thirds of the
labor force in about 100 projects that would concentrate on the
development of rural infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
The projects involved the building of roads, livestock-dipping
facilities, micro irrigation schemes, dams, shearing sheds,
markets, storage facilities and classrooms.
</P>
<P>
The areas targeted were poor regions in Kwazulu-Natal, Eastern
Cape and Northern Provinces.
</P>
<P>
Radebe said the program would emphasize vocational training
such as building and plumbing skills for those participating in
the projects.
</P>
<P>
The Public Works Department would also seek to develop the
management skills of local authorities to enable them to take
over and successfully run the projects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
