<DOCNO> XIE19980109.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria's Forex Demand Shoots Up at Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Foreign exchange demand at
Nigeria's official foreign exchange swap market has shored up to
a new high of more than 100 million U.S. Dollars following the
release of this year's budget.
</P>
<P>
Results of transactions at the Autonomous Foreign Exchange
Market (AFEM), where the Central Bank sells foreign exchange to
selected commercial banks, totalled 100.254 million Dollars in
the year's first trading day Wednesday, three days after the
budget was announced.
</P>
<P>
The demand was shared among 62 out of the 80 banks selected to
partake in the market, the Central Bank said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The exchange rate stood at 75 Naira, the Nigerian currency, to
one Dollar, the same as at the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
Such a demand, the highest in eight months, was described as
reasonable by analysts who said it was the result of the new
budget which is full of incentive to promote production this year
if well implemented.
</P>
<P>
According to Finance Minister Anthony Ani, the Central Bank
made 51 interventions in the weekly trading at AFEM last year and
disbursed a net amount of 2.989 billion Dollars, 733 million
Dollars less than the total supply.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the parallel foreign exchange market, the organized
non-official trading place open to individuals, reflected the
current happenings at AFEM.
</P>
<P>
The Dollar now exchanges at about 80 Naira compared with 82
Naira last week at the exchange bureaus. 
</P>
</TEXT>
