<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT January 9 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO -- More than 300 people were injured in Tokyo and
neighboring prefectures in accidents linked to the area's heaviest
snowfall in two years.
</P>
<P>
The snow, which started Thursday afternoon, peaked that night
but continued through early Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
Many trains were halted and domestic flights delayed or
canceled as the Meteorological Agency issued snow
warnings. (Japan-Snow)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
OTTAWA -- A prolonged ice storm forced Canada's national
capital region of Ottawa to declare a state of emergency Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The freezing rain, coupled with strong wind, has brought havocs
to the region, where falling ice-coated tree branches littered
roads and cut numerous power lines.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of homes have been hit with power failures since
Tuesday, which seriously disrupted people's life in a country that
nearly everything from garage doors to stoves are operated with
electricity. (Canada Ottawa Storm)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ROME -- Turkey and seven European Union countries agreed
Thursday to strengthen efforts to curb the inflow of Kurdish
immigrants via Italy's poorly checked borders and intensify their
fights against organized crime.
</P>
<P>
Police chiefs and security officials from Italy, Turkey,
Germany, France, the Netherlands, Austria, Belgium and Greece came
up with the measures with a day-long meeting in Rome in response
to the recent influx of more than 1,200 Kurds into
Italy. (Italy-Kurds)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JAKARTA -- Panic buying hit stores across Indonesia's capital
city of Jakarta Thursday after a dramatic fall in the value of
the national currency and many people were worried about a
possible price hike in the near future.
</P>
<P>
Long queues were seen at most supermarkets with basic
foodstuffs such as rice and instant noodles vanishing from
shelves. (Indonesia-Panic Buying)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
