<DOCNO> XIE19980109.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines to Intensify Economic Diplomacy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 9 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines will intensify
its economic diplomacy drive and push for the establishment of the
proposed Cambodia-Laos-Philippines-Thailand-Vietnam Growth Polygon
this year, the country's top diplomat said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
In a briefing for the diplomatic press corps, Foreign Affairs
Secretary Domingo Siazon said the strategy is intended to
"mobilize external resources in support of national development."
</P>
<P>
The envisioned polygon is expected to accelerate the
development of the proposed Northwestern Luzon Growth Area in the
northern Philippines and link the area to continental Southeast
Asia under a regime of more enhanced trade traffic and economic
exchange.
</P>
<P>
Siazon stressed that economic diplomacy will remain a major
pillar of the Philippine foreign policy and will be further
intensified to boost the country's economic relations with its
partners through trade and investments.
</P>
<P>
The prevailing global and regional political and economic
environment, including the currency turmoil sweeping Southeast
Asia, offers both challenges and opportunities for the Philippines
to maximize the benefits from its economic diplomacy initiatives,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Economic diplomacy, spearheaded by President Fidel Ramos, is
largely credited for the country's economic turnaround since 1993,
according to Siazon.
</P>
<P>
The country's economic upsurge continued through up to the
third quarter of 1997 despite high interest rates, a sustained dip
in the value of the peso and the adverse effects on agriculture of
the El Nino phenomenon, Siazon said.
</P>
<P>
"Business sentiment remains largely unaffected and
multinational companies and other investors remain bullish on the
prospects of the country as an investment destination," he
declared.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
