<HEADLINE> Lebanese Foreign Minister to Visit Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Foreign Minister Farez
Boueiz is scheduled to visit Moscow next month to discuss with the
Russian side the Middle East peace process and bilateral ties, the
local Daily Star reported today.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference Thursday, Russian ambassador to Lebanon
Oleg Peressypkine said that Boueiz, who will start his visit on
February 2, has planned to head a delegation of business people to
seek opportunities of cooperation with Russian counterparts.
</P>
<P>
"The minister may also sign a protocol allowing the Russian
Foreign Ministry to publish the documents of the Russian
consulate that had been operated in Beirut during Ottoman rule,"
Peressypkine said.
</P>
<P>
Asked about Israel's proposal to pull out from south Lebanon
under the United Nations Security Council resolution 425, the
Russian ambassador declined to comment "before we study the
suggestion."
</P>
<P>
He said that "a pullout is always welcome, but we have to know
what Israel wants as guarantees."
</P>
<P>
With regard to the Middle East peace talks, Peressypkine
reaffirmed that "Russia's mediation is not half-hearted and the
Lebanese minister's visit comes in line with Moscow's role as a
sponsor of the negotiations." 
</P>
