<HEADLINE> East China's Province Economy Maintains Strong Momentum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANCHANG, January 9 (Xinhua) -- East China's Jiangxi Province
achieved an 11.5 percent increase in economic growth in the
January-November period in 1997, according to a provincial
official.
</P>
<P>
Shu Shengyou, governor of the province said that Jiangxi
produced 171.5 billion yuan in GDP in 1997, up 25 billion yuan to
that of the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The province also maintained a balanced in revenue and
expenditure. The retail price fell by 6.9 percent to that of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Fiscal revenue in Jiangxi reached 13.61 billion yuan in 1997,
up by ten percent over that of 1996. By November of 1997, total
bank savings in Jiangxi reached 104.6 billion yuan, up 14.3
billion yuan over that of 1996. The province had utilized 650
million US dollars of foreign investment by the end of 1997.
</P>
<P>
The provincial governor attributed these achievements to good
agriculture harvest, enhanced effort in reform of state-owned
enterprises, and more smooth operation of key projects in Jiangxi.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, Jiangxi produced 17.7 million tons
of grain last year, setting a new record. The output of some other
agriculture products output also increased, including oil-bearing
crops, cotton, meat, aquatic products and fruits.  
</P>
</TEXT>
