<DOCNO> XIE19980109.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanian VP Calls for Control of Cholera </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian Vice-President
Omar Juma has urged Dar residents to observe hygiene so as to
curb the spread of cholera which may worsen this year due to
excessive seasonal rains linked to El Nino weather pattern.
</P>
<P>
During a tour Thursday to inspect health centers for cholera
victims in Temeke, Ilala, and Kinodoni districts of the capital,
Juma was informed that more than 200 residents in Dar died of
cholera last year and the death toll is likely to double this
year.
</P>
<P>
District medical officers briefed the vice president that the
worst hit groups were those low-income earners, people who built
their houses in the valleys and those who use stagnant water, The
Guardian reported today.
</P>
<P>
"It is shameful for the nation to have such a disease because
it implies that we are still living in filth," the vice president
was quoted by the paper as saying.
</P>
<P>
The epidemic also discourages foreign investors, hurting the
country's economic development, he said.
</P>
<P>
Juma appealed to the people living in the valleys to quit the
places for their own safety, saying that heavy rains are around
the corner and they will become victims of floods at any time.
</P>
<P>
Meteorological departments predicted that heavy rains starting
early last month will continue till April.
</P>
<P>
A major reason why cholera has persisted for a long time in
the city is that residents do not have a clean habit. Ailing
sewerage systems, the scarcity of clean water and haphazard
construction of houses are also to blame, medical officers said.
</P>
<P>
The vice president has called for the establishment of special
committees to help carry out health regulations, which is
imperative to help residents control the spread of the epidemic.
</P>
<P>
No government in the world could clean people's houses, he
said.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, 36,182 people in Tanzania contracted cholera and
2,124 people died of the disease, lastest statistics indicate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
