<HEADLINE> EU Bans Fish Import From E. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, January 9 (Xinhua) -- The European Union has imposed
a ban on fish import from east Africa including Uganda, Tanzania,
Kenya and Mozambique, local media reported today.
</P>
<P>
The ban came into effect on December 23, confirmed Bernard
Ryelandt, a European Commission official.
</P>
<P>
The emergency ban due to cholera epidemic is provisional and
will be reviewed before the end of February 1998 to determine
whether to extend it for further period or not, he said.
</P>
<P>
Byelandt described the provisional ban as a ''tip of the
iceberg'' concerning the hygiene condition in fish processing.
</P>
<P>
He said the EU is ready to consider extending financial
assistance to affected countries to enable them to upgrade the
hygienic conditions of fish processing.
</P>
<P>
Fish export became Uganda's second major foreign exchange
earner after coffee in 1996. Its major markets include Europe,
Japan and the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
