<HEADLINE> U.S. Commodities Fall on Futures Market on Asian Woes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Wheat, corn, soybean and
lean hog futures retreated sharply Thursday on the Chicago Board
of Trade, according to news reaching here.
</P>
<P>
Wheat for March delivery fell 8 1-2 cents to dlrs 3.20 1-2 a
bushel while corn dropped 5 cents to dlrs 2.58 1-2 a
bushel. Soybeans for January delivery fell 10 cents to dlrs 6.59
3-4 a bushel and February lean hogs fell 1.20 cents to 56.45 cents
a pound.
</P>
<P>
Analysts attribute the sharp fall of prices to the concerns
that the Asian economic crisis will lead to reduced American
exports.
</P>
<P>
They said that the U.S. dollar has been rising against Asian
currencies and making American commodities more expensive.
</P>
<P>
Figures released by the U.S. Agriculture Department show that
wheat export last week were 69 percent below the previous week,
while corn export fell 44 percent.
</P>
<P>
The demand for these commodities remains light though the
Agriculture Department announced late Monday that, in a bid to
keep goods flowing overseas, it had offered export subsidies to
several Asian nations currently hit by a currency crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
