<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe to Expand Victim Friendly Court System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 9 (Xinhua) -- The victim-friendly court system
has proved successful and the Zimbabwean government is now
seeking donor funding to expand it to other areas, Minister of
Justice Emmerson Mnangagwa said.
</P>
<P>
The minister was speaking after witnessing a court session in
the victim-friendly court at Harare magistrates' court during a
visit Thursday with his visiting Swedish counterpart, Laila
Freivalds.
</P>
<P>
The Swedish minister, who arrived last Sunday, said she was
impressed on the victim-friendly court system.
</P>
<P>
Mnangagwa said the victim-friendly system, which was
introduced last year, was working perfectly. He noted that rape
victims were now able to give evidence freely.
</P>
<P>
Under the new system, a victim would sit in a different room
and give evidence while she is monitored by a Camera. The victim
communicates through an intermediary, who is either a social
worker or interpreter, who then relays the evidence to the main
courtroom.
</P>
<P>
Mnangagwa said, with the success of the system, the government
now wanted to expand it. Cameras and television monitors, among
other gadgets, were required for the system.
</P>
<P>
Once a rape victim had completed giving evidence in the
victim-friendly court, the case would then revert to the open
court.
</P>
<P>
The Swedish minister said the victim-friendly court system was
also used in her country.
</P>
<P>
However, it was different from the local system in that, in
her country, the victim was interviewed and filmed before the
proceedings.
</P>
<P>
In the previous system, victims sometimes broke down and
failed to give evidence in the presence of the suspected
culprits. "The new system is very good. I know how difficult it
is to deal with such cases, and get evidence to convict," she
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980109.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
