<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Shuts Down 65,000 Polluting Factories </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 9 (Xinhua) -- China closed more than 65,000
factories considered serious polluters from July of 1996 to
September of 1997, according to the statistics released by the
State Environmental Protection Agency.
 The closed factories are mainly among 15 types of small, serious
polluters designated by the State Council.
</P>
<P>
Among those closed were small leather tanning factories,
printing and dyeing mills, coking plants using outdated production
processes and paper mills with annual production capacities of
5,000 tons or less.
</P>
<P>
Through this move, China can reduce the emission of nearly two
billion tons of wastewater, 42.3 billion cubic meters of waste gas
and more than 81 million tons of solid waste every year.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-three province-level areas -- including Beijing,
Shanghai and Tianjin -- have closed nearly all the 15 types of
small factories. Sources say that all those in the country's key
pollution-control regions such as the Huaihe, Haihe and Liaohe
river valleys have been shut down.
</P>
<P>
Governments at all levels have taken steps to prevent closed
factories from resuming production. More than 1,000 plants had
resumed production after closure, and more than 93 percent of
those were closed again.
</P>
<P>
Some provinces have also closed polluting factories not
included on the State Council's list. East China's Shandong
Province has began to close paper mills with annual production
capacities below 10,000 tons, to further control pollution.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980109.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya's Coffee Output to Increase Slightly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's coffee production is
projected to increase this year to about 74,858 tons, compared
with 68,369 tons last year, the Daily Nation reported today.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Flavian Mwangi, Chairman of the Mild Coffee
Traders Association, as warning that the quality of the coffee
may be low because of the effect of the heavy rains since last
November caused by the El Nino phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
He noted that last year's production was a 30 percent drop
from the 1995/96 output of 97,575 tons.
</P>
<P>
Coffee prices were firm in the 1996/97 year with the overall
annual average price topping 117.24 U.S. Dollars per 50-kg bag,
thus improving the farmers' return throughout the year despite a
decline in coffee production.
</P>
<P>
Mwangi pointed out at an annual general meeting held recently
that liberalization in the coffee sector gave farmers a bigger
choice following the licensing of more dealers and the
introduction of a multi-auction system.
</P>
<P>
The chairman said that as a result of liberalization three
more coffee auctioneers had been licensed by the Coffee Board of
Kenya, bringing the number to four.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the coffee industry was set to benefit this
year from the positive effects of the liberalization policy being
implemented by the sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
