<DOCNO> XIE19980109.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Trade Deficit Narrows in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia recorded a trade
deficit of 700 million ringgit (152.17 million U.S. dollars)
between January and November 1997, much lower than the 1.3 billion
ringgit (282.6 million dollars) a year earlier, official figures
show.
</P>
<P>
If trade in "lumpy" items (aircraft and ships/tankers,
including accessories) was excluded from the import and re-export
data, there would have been a surplus of 5 billion ringgit (1.086
billion dollars) in the period, according to the November 1997
trade figures released by the Statistics Department here Friday.
</P>
<P>
During the 11 months, Malaysia's total export earnings grew by
10.4 percent to 198.4 billion ringgit (43.13 billion dollars) from
179.7 billion ringgit (39.06 billion dollars) in the corresponding
period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
During the period under review, total imports increased by 10
percent to 199.1 billion ringgit (43.28 billion dollars) over the
181 billion ringgit (39.34 billion dollars) a year ago.
</P>
<P>
The United States, Japan and Singapore remained the top three
trading partners, which collectively accounted for 51.5 percent of
Malaysia's total trade during the January-November 1997 period.
</P>
<P>
In the month of November 1997, Malaysia registered a trade
surplus of 600 million ringgit (130.43 million dollars), with
exports expanding 30.9 percent to 21.6 billion ringgit (4.695
billion dollars) and imports by 23.1 percent to 21 billion
ringgit (4.565 billion dollars).  
