<HEADLINE> Chinese Coal Provider Dealing With Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, January 9 (Xinhua) -- China's coal-rich province of
Shanxi had further success in its poverty war in 1997 when it
helped 850,000 farmers provide food and clothing for themselves.
</P>
<P>
The gains came after a tough battle with a severe
drought. Poverty relief projects involved building terraced fields
on mountain slopes, introducing greenhouse farming, and planting
fruit trees.
</P>
<P>
Some 20,000 government cadres were sent to villages to help
with these projects.
</P>
<P>
An official from the State Statistics Bureau estimates that
about eight million people were lifted above the subsistence level
nationwide in 1997. 
</P>
