<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Government to Borrow More to Help Exporters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 9 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government will borrow
another 600 million U.S. dollars from overseas to help exporters,
according to the newspaper The Nation Friday.
</P>
<P>
The move followed a 500 million dollar loan from a Japanese
consortium to boost Thailand's exports, on which much hope has
been placed to get the country out of its current economic
recession.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Thailand's central bank has also agreed to increase
its contribution to the credit facility of the Export-Import Bank,
to help alleviate the burden on commercial banks and boost export
liquidity.
</P>
<P>
Last year, despite the baht's steep plunge since its float on
July 2, export performance and earnings failed to meet
expectations.
</P>
<P>
Exporters complained that they had difficulty getting loans,
because some commercial banks refused to lend to them as the banks
themselves could not maintain their capital funds at the level
required by the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
Others were prohibited by the high interest rates introduced
for the defense of the baht.  
</P>
</TEXT>
