<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Plans to Build Giant Power Station </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's largest power station
will be built on the Sengwa coal fields in Gokwe, north Zimbabwe
at a cost of a staggering 27.75 billion Zimbabwe Dollars or 1.63
billion U.S. Dollars, ''the Herald'' paper reported today.
</P>
<P>
The project will be the country's single largest investment
since independence in 1980 and is expected to come on stream in
six years.
</P>
<P>
This follows the awarding by the government of exclusive
negotiating rights for the proposed giant power station to three
interested parties: Britain's National Power, Rio Tinto Zimbabwe
and the Zimbabwe Electricity Supply Authority.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Transport and Energy Enos Chikowore said yesterday
that the multi-billion-Dollar project would see the development
of a coal mine by Rio Tinto at Sengwa in the Zambezi valley near
Lake Kariba to fuel the power station.
</P>
<P>
The station itself would have an installed capacity of 1,400
megawatts, enough to supply 1.4 billion units of energy in an
hour.
</P>
<P>
The new station should be able to supply about a third of the
country's anticipated requirements at the time and just over half
of the current demand.
</P>
<P>
The thermal power station would be built in such a way as to
minimize environmental degradation through pollution and in line
with environmental standards acceptable to the government, World
Bank, and the policies of both Rio Tinto and the British Utility.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
