<HEADLINE> W. Bank Backs Drainage Expanding Project in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, January 9 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank has agreed to
provide Uganda with 4 billion Uganda Shillings (some 3.5 million
U.S. Dollars) to support a project aimed at expanding drainage in
Kampala, "The Monitor" reported today.
</P>
<P>
Nakivubo drainage from Makerere-Bwaise area to Lake Victoria
via Port Bellis was built in 1950's and is narrowed down and
heavily silted, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Abraham Byandala, the city engineer, told the paper that the
new plan of Kampala City Council (KCC) for the channel is to
expand its capacity to run-off water in phases.
</P>
<P>
The first phase is to cover the lower reaches of the channel
under tenders starting in the first two weeks in December last
year, he added.
</P>
<P>
KCC's initial plans for the channel include building barriers
to sieve out refuse and avoid silting. But the barriers caused
overflows and floods, one of the reasons for cholera epidemic
during recent heavy rains. 
</P>
</TEXT>
