<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Vows to Build More Housing for University Teachers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 9 (Xinhua) -- The State Education Commission
announced here today that the country will construct more
apartments for university teachers.
</P>
<P>
Ji Baocheng, director of the commission's Planning Department,
said the housing difficulty for teachers has been eased in rural
schools and urban primary and high schools. University teachers,
especially young and middle-aged professors, are facing severe
problems, however, Ji said.
</P>
<P>
China has a time-honored tradition of respecting teachers and
scholars, which broke down during the "Cultural Revolution"
(1966-76). The government's new strategy of invigorating the
country by means of science and education has given priority to
the development of the educational sector.
</P>
<P>
Building apartments for teachers is a primary consideration,
according to the government policy.
</P>
<P>
In the 1991-96 period, China spent 48 billion yuan (6 billion
U.S. dollars) building 84 million square meters of housing for
teachers. But the floor space shared by a university teacher is
less than eight square meters shared by urban citizens on
average.
</P>
<P>
Ji said that both central and local governments will allocate
more funds this year to build apartments for teachers, and a
market economy will be introduced to push the housing reform in
universities. Old apartment buildings also will be renovated for
use by teachers, he said.
</P>
<P>
A high-profile conference will be held soon to discuss detailed
measures, Ji said.
</P>
<P>
Housing has been an age-old problem in China as a result of
indifference toward teachers' jobs. The government has been
pursuing a policy of asking people to respect teachers, Ji said,
and economic development has laid a solid foundation for
constructing more apartment buildings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
