<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain, Sweden Give S. Africa Arms Deal Deadline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Britain and Sweden have
given South Africa a six-month deadline to take a decision on
national arms procurement, or risk losing more than four billion
U.S. Dollars in counter-trade over the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
According to "The Star" newspaper today, the ultimatum, which
expires on July 31, was given Thursday, one day after South
Africa's Defense Department said there would be a delay in
deciding on a 2.04-billion-Dollar arms deal because further
information was needed on particular products being offered.
</P>
<P>
The South African parliament approved a plan to re-equip the
National Defense Force, giving the green light to the purchase of
corvettes, submarines, jet aircraft, helicopters and main battle
tanks.
</P>
<P>
Britain and Sweden are offering 48 Gripen jet fighters and
trainers manufactured by a joint venture between British
Aerospace and Saab Aerospace, while the British have also offered
independently the Hawk New Generation jet trainers.
</P>
<P>
British Aerospace representative in South Africa, Allan
MacDonald, warned that a delay in the decision would not only
harm the local defense industry, but also result in export
losses, changed investment plans and the loss of socio-economic
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
Saab President Bengt Halse said Swedish interests alone were
prepared to immediately invest 122 million Dollars in various
industrial participation ventures, which would include
socio-economic projects such as education.
</P>
<P>
Reports said six countries including Britain, Canada, France,
Germany, Italy and Spain were short-listed by the South African
Defense Department as potential arms suppliers.
</P>
<P>
But the Defense Department refused to elaborate until the
relevant countries have been approached officially. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
