<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Beat Legacy of Poor Matric Result: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 9 (Xinhua) -- South African Education
Minister Sibusiso Bengu has expressed disappointment with the
1997 matriculation results, and vowed to take decisive measures
to get national education improved.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters in Cape Town Thursday, Bengu said no
single factor could be blamed for poor performances by schools,
teachers, or pupils - but it was important to draw attention to
some of these factors.
</P>
<P>
He said many of the matric candidates were poorly prepared for
the examinations and at some schools no learning or teaching took
place at all last year.
</P>
<P>
As long as this went on, there was little doubt that many
pupils would continue to fail and this could not be allowed to
happen, he said.
</P>
<P>
On school management, Bengu said schools should fire teachers
who failed to show commitment to improving the success rate,
stressing that teachers had to pull up their socks or be fired.
</P>
<P>
South Africa could not afford to pay salaries to teachers not
committed to teaching and who did not achieve what was expected
of them, the minister added.
</P>
<P>
Bengu made assurance last year that national matric result
would not worsen from the 54.7 percent past rate of 1996.
</P>
<P>
However, last year's national pass rate was 47.1 percent, with
provincial declines ranging from 19.6 percentage points in North
West Province to 1.7 percentage points in Mpumalanga Province.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
