<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Star Oil Company Reports Steady Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 9 (Xinhua) -- The China National Star
Petroleum Corp. (CNSPC), the country's third largest oil company,
has forged cooperative ties with oil companies and research
institutes in more than 60 countries since its establishment one
year ago.
</P>
<P>
President Zhu Jiazhen said CNSPC is engaged in a number of
international oil exploration and drilling projects in the Gulf of
Mexico, the North Sea, the Sea of Japan, Russia and Cote d'Ivoire.
</P>
<P>
He said the Sino-Japanese Geological Engineering Corp.
(SJGEC), a joint venture between the CNSPC and a Japanese firm, is
now operational. Petroleum equipment manufactured by SJGEC is
being exported to the United States, Canada, South America and
Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
The CNSPC has also joined Australian companies in exploring and
marketing coal-bed methane gas in Shanxi and Shaanxi provinces in
north China. Other projects include a joint assessment of Hedong
coal-bed methane reserves and a technical cooperation project with
U.S. firms on the development of the Yakela oil and gas field, and
a joint project with Japanese companies to verify oil reserves
in the Songhuajiang and Liaohe river basins in northeast China.
</P>
<P>
Zhu said the CNSPC is striving for annual oil and gas
production of 10 million tons by 2010. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
