<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan to Ask U.S. to Return Money for Aircraft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Foreign Minister
Gohar Ayub Khan has said Pakistan will go to court in the United
States in the next few weeks to get back 656 million U.S. dollars
it had paid for 28 undelivered F-16 fighters.
</P>
<P>
All preparations in this regard have been made, the foreign
minister was quoted Friday by the leading English daily The Nation
as saying. "We have got the approval of the competent authority
(prime minister) to go to the American courts."
</P>
<P>
Ayub Khan told the paper on Thursday that "we will hire best
lawyers because 656 million dollars are stuck up."
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister said all papers and legal work for filing
a suit against the U.S. administration have been prepared by
Pakistan's legal experts.
</P>
<P>
The delivery of the F-16s was stopped by the U.S.
administration in the early 1990s after the enforcement of the
Pressler Amendment, which restrained the administration from
providing military hardware to Pakistan, alleging that the country
was implementing a nuclear program.
</P>
<P>
Ayub Khan said Pakistan was reluctant to go to court as U.S.
President Bill Clinton had been scheduled to visit Pakistan in
February or March and Pakistan was expecting something from
Clinton in this regard. However, Clinton's planned visit has now
been delayed.
</P>
<P>
Ayub Khan also said that even if the U.S. administration agrees
to return the money, it will have to seek congress appropriation
which is an uphill task.
</P>
<P>
In this situation the only option for Pakistan is to go to
court to get back the money, said the foreign minister.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
