<HEADLINE> Cleaner Drinking Water for Shanghai Residents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, January 9 (Xinhua) -- The second phase water
diversion project from the upper reaches of the Huangpu River, the
biggest river flowing across the city, has been completed,
bringing cleaner drinking water to the city's residents.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing-based "China Environmental News" reported that the
project can supply the city with five million cubic meters of
water each day.
</P>
<P>
All the city's water plants are diverting water from the upper
reaches of the Huangpu River, besides the Yangtze River, after the
completion of the water diversion project, the paper reported.
</P>
<P>
It is part of the municipality's drinking-water improvement
project that began in July 1994, that is expected to cost three
billion yuan, with the help of 110 million US dollars in World
Bank loans.
</P>
<P>
The Huangpu River is the city's No.1 water resource.
</P>
<P>
The decline in water quality standard in the lower reaches of
the Huangpu River has been a major scourge for local residents and
industrial and agricultural production. So, in recent years,
Shanghai has adopted a series of measures to improve its
environment, including a number of waste water treatment
projects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
