<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Heaviest Snowfall in Two Years Hits Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, January 9 (Xinhua) -- More than 300 people were injured
in Tokyo and neighboring prefectures in accidents linked to the
area's heaviest snowfall in two years.
</P>
<P>
The snow, which started Thursday afternoon, peaked that night
but continued through early Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
Many trains were halted and domestic flights delayed or
canceled as the Meteorological Agency issued snow warnings.
</P>
<P>
Police and fire fighters said that more than 300 people were
injured in the capital and seven neighboring prefectures from
slipping on the snow and snow-related traffic accidents.
</P>
<P>
There were 167 snow-related car accidents in the metropolitan
area, the Metropolitan Police Department said.
</P>
<P>
The snowfall reached 15 centimeters in the Otemachi business
district in the heart of Tokyo, and 20 centimeters in Yokohama,
southwest of Tokyo, according to the Meteorological Agency.
</P>
<P>
It was the heaviest snowfall since February 18, 1996, when 14
centimeters of snow blanketed the area, said an official of the
agency.
</P>
<P>
Tokyo's heaviest snowfall reached 33 centimeters and occurred
on February 15, 1951. 
</P>
</TEXT>
