<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Plane Crash Kills 3 in NZ </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Three people died in a plane
crash in New Zealand Friday, TVNZ reported.
</P>
<P>
The light plane, belonging to Waterwings Airways, was flying
from Te Anua in the South Island to the tourist town of Queentown,
200 km north of Te Anau. It went down into a dense bush near Mount
Prospect, 20 km north of Te Anau.
</P>
<P>
The three people on board, the pilot and two Japanese tourists,
all died in the crash.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted police as saying that the pilot was
experienced, and they suspected bad weather caused the disaster.
</P>
<P>
A search team was ready to go into the bush to recover the
bodies, but they were hampered from doing so by the bad weather.
The area was shrouded in fog and rain, and rescue work could not
start until Saturday, the report said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
