<DOCNO> XIE19980109.0245 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mahathir Confident of Moderate Economic Recovery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad Friday expressed his confidence that moderate
economic recovery at an acceptable level could be attained within
six to 12 months provided Malaysians show full confidence in the
ringgit and the local stock market.
</P>
<P>
"If we have the confidence and don't resort to, say for
instance, converting ringgit into U.S. dollars or other foreign
currencies, then recovery will be easy because we ourselves don't
contribute to the depreciation of our own currency," he said when
appearing as guest on TV3's morning talk show "Malaysia Today"
which discussed consumers and the economy.
</P>
<P>
During the 90-minute program, the prime minister responded to
various questions sent by e-mail or facsimile from viewers who
wanted to know when the current economic turmoil would end.
</P>
<P>
Acknowledging that it would be impossible to see the economy
revitalized to its former strength as before the ringgit started
weakening last July, Mahathir said he was confident moderate
recovery at an acceptable level could be attained if the people
adopt specific measures.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said Malaysians should have confidence in local banks
and save more in local banks and financial institutions to help
shore up national reserves.
</P>
<P>
"If we all do that, I'm confident we'll recover, not to our
original level, but to a moderately sufficient level, perhaps
within six months or a year," he said.
</P>
<P>
To a question whether Malaysia would eventually turn to the IMF
for help, he said if "we receive IMF aid, we would not be able to
control our economy and would throw it open to foreign domination
whereby they would come in and buy our banks and companies at
cheap prices," which would then amount to "economic colonialism".
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said Malaysia has adequate foreign reserves to finance
its requirements and sustain growth amid the current economic
problems.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said that the measures to build up reserves include
increasing exports, cutting imports where necessary and buying the
ringgit.
</P>
<P>
He urged the people to have more faith in the country's
economic resilience, saying the fact that Malaysia had not asked
for financial aid from the International Monetary Fund (IMF)
showed that the economy was stable.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said a further positive indication of the economy was
that Malaysia's debts were not large.
</P>
<P>
According to an announcement by the State Bank Wednesday, the
country's total foreign debt (short, medium-term and long-term)
was 45.2 billion U.S. dollars, accounting for 42 percent of
Malaysia's gross domestic product, and out of the total debt, the
short-term debt accounted for only 30 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980109.0246 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam's Farm Labour Demand Rising </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam's need for farm labourers
will increase until the year 2000 due to a lack of modern
agricultural technology, Vietnam's English language daily the
"Vietnam News" quoted officials as saying in its Friday edition.
</P>
<P>
With an annual growth rate of 10 percent estimated for the
Gross Domestic Product (GDP) during the 1996 to 2000 period, the
demand for an industrialized workforce may rise slightly in
Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
The Agricultural sector, which currently accounts for 70
percent of the population, will continue to be labour intensive,
said the report.
</P>
<P>
By the year 2000, Vietnam is expected to have more than 47.7
million people of working age. Of these, 44.6 million will be
employed full-time, with about 3.1 million people jobless.
</P>
<P>
The pool of working age people includes 1.7 million students
and 2.3 million housewives.
</P>
<P>
Vietnamese labour authorities have called for more investment
to develop infrastructure in an effort to attract labour intensive
industries that will concentrate on agricultural production in the
slowly developing areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
