<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Provides Relief for Refugees on Thailand- </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Australia announced Friday it
was contributing a further one million Australian dollars (650,000
US dollars) in humanitarian relief to Myanmar's refugees residing
in camps on the Thailand-Burma border.
</P>
<P>
Australian Foreign Minister Alexander Downer said the aid is
for over 115,000 refugees composed of largely the Karen ethnic
minority but also the Mon and Karenni peoples.
</P>
<P>
Australian funds, which are being provided through the
country's official aid agency AusAID's humanitarian relief
program, will provide food, mosquito nets, firewood, blankets and
basic health care, the foreign minister said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
He said the relief program will be implemented in partnership
with Australian non-governmental organizations, including the
National Council of Churches in Australia and Community Aid
Abroad.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980109.0250 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ice Storm Forces Ottawa to Declare State of Emergency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, January 8 (Xinhua) -- A prolonged ice storm forced
Canada's national capital region of Ottawa to declare a state of
emergency Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The freezing rain, coupled with strong wind, has brought havocs to
the region, where falling ice-coated tree branches littered roads and
cut numerous power lines.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of homes have been hit with power failures since Tuesday,
which seriously disrupted people's life in a country that nearly
everything from garage doors to stoves are operated with electricity.
</P>
<P>
The community where Xinhua correspondents live have been coping
without electricity on Tuesday and again on Thursday. Power has
yet to be restored here at press time.
</P>
<P>
Across the region, more than 20 relief centers have opened by
Thursday afternoon, where people can have access to shelter, soup,
food and warm sleep.
</P>
<P>
"The state of emergency is to recognize the seriousness of the
situation," said Regional Chair Bob Chiarelli.
</P>
<P>
All schools are closed today and tomorrow. The government
is asking people to avoid going out as much as possible. Large
companies and government departments encouraged its employees to
stay at home.
</P>
<P>
Traffic accidents were reported in and outside this city, and
some artery highways have been closed to traffic.
</P>
<P>
East of the Ottawa River, the situation in Quebec province is
even worse. By Thursday evening, two million people in Quebec have
been rendered without electricity.
</P>
<P>
Though Quebec Hydro tried its best to restore power to
customers, the task has proved too tough for thousands of its
workers, who worked 16 hours a day in the last few days.
</P>
<P>
Local forecast said there will still be icy rain in eastern
Ontario and Quebec province on Saturday. But things will improve
Saturday and Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
