<HEADLINE> Inspection of Boeing 737s for Missing Units Ordered </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Federal Aviation
Administration (FAA) Thursday ordered airlines to inspect Boeing
737s to check hinge fasteners that discovered missing from a jet
that crashed in Indonesia last month.
</P>
<P>
The FAA requires a visual inspection of the horizontal
stabilizers on Boeing 737s in the 300-, 400- and 500-series
models. The inspection will involve more than 200 planes.
</P>
<P>
It asked airlines to look for missing fasteners and check that
all bolts connecting hinges are secured properly and report to it
the results within five days.
</P>
<P>
The order was made after a preliminary investigation into the
crash of a Singapore-owned SilkAir Boeing 737 on December 19. The
plane crashed onto the island of Sumatra during a flight from
Jakarta to Singapore, killing all 104 people aboard.
</P>
<P>
The FAA said 26 fasteners on the plane's horizontal stabilizer
were missing.
</P>
<P>
But it said there was no evidence linking the missing or loose
fasteners to the cause of the accident. 
</P>
</TEXT>
