<HEADLINE> Australian Wool Prices Drop Slightly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 9 (Xinhua) -- The Asian financial crisis and
the slide of the Australian dollar meant confusion and uncertainty
were the dominant features of this week's resumption of wool
sales, the Australian Council of Wool Exporters (ACWE) said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
"Confusion and uncertainty, not surprisingly, marked the
resumption of auction sales in Melbourne and Fremantle this week,
and prices were affected accordingly," ACWE said in its weekly
market statement.
</P>
<P>
The eastern market indicator fell 15 Australian cents from its
pre-Christmas level to close the week at 683 Australian cents a
kilogram clean with the western market indicator dropping 11
Australian cents to finish at 633 Australian cents a kilogram
clean.
</P>
<P>
The new AWEX national price indicator ended the week at 717
Australian cents a kilogram clean, reflecting a decrease of 13
Australian cents.
</P>
<P>
Falls of 12 Australian cents and 25 Australian cents occurred
in the southern and western price indicators which ended in levels
of 707 Australian cents and 685 Australian cents a kilogram clean
respectively.
</P>
<P>
"The market commenced on a very tentative note with buyers not
knowing how the continuing economic and currency crises in Asia
would affect market confidence and demand overall," ACWE said.
</P>
<P>
ACWE said the drop in the Australian dollar was positive but
had a downside because there was uncertainty about when stability
would return.
</P>
<P>
"The strengthening of the Australian dollar towards the end of
this week's selling probably contributed to the wool market
stabilizing on Thursday." ACWE said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
