<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Foreign Reserves Stand at 21.4 Billion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Governor of Bank Indonesia
(central bank) Soedradjad Djiwandono said the government currently
has gross foreign assets of 21.4 billion US dollars and it would
continue efforts to stem the rupiah's fall.
</P>
<P>
"The president (Soeharto) is closely watching the latest
developments. The government will continue efforts to overcome the
rupiah's fall. I hope this thing well pass quickly," Djiwandono
said here Thursday night after meeting with President Soeharto.
</P>
<P>
He said the government is persuading Indonesian exporters to
convert their dollars into the rupiah in order to ease the current
economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah hit a record low of 11,000 against the US dollar in
late trading Thursday. The rupiah has lost about 300 percent of
its value against the greenback since early July last year.
</P>
<P>
The central bank governor said he was convinced the rupiah's
weakness was temporary and it will recover to more realistic
levels speedily.
</P>
<P>
The sharp fall in the rupiah was caused more by market
sentiment rather than the country's economic fundamentals, he
added.
</P>
<P>
However, local dealers attributed the drop of the rupiah to the
worsening of public confidence in the economy and the
International Monetary Fund's (IMF's) disappointment over the
government's programs in coping with the monetary crisis.
</P>
