<HEADLINE> Currency Turmoil Too Much for Thai Economy: Banker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's banker of the year
1997 said that the ongoing currency turmoil has inflicted such
rapid deterioration on the Thai economy that he doubts Thailand
alone has the power to stop it.
</P>
<P>
Chulakorn Singhakhowin, 48, who won the honor for transforming
a sick, owner-managed Bank of Asia into a healthy and profitable
professionally-managed financial institution, said no economy
could sustain the extreme currency swings such as those which the
baht is experiencing.
</P>
<P>
The baht has lost more than 100 percent of its value against
the US dollar in six months' time since its float.
</P>
<P>
Chulakorn, who has been president of Bank of Asia for five
years, said in an interview with the Nation published Friday that
with the baht's unabated rapid degeneration, corporate
bankruptcies and financial institutions' non-performing loans will
skyrocket.
</P>
<P>
He believed that if the speed and depth of the current economic
deterioration continue at the same rate throughout Asia and does
not stop, even the now-strong western economies will soon be badly
affected.
</P>
<P>
He said even though the 17.2 billion US dollar bailout program
of the International Monetary Fund (IMF) has been partially
implemented, confidence has not been restored, because no one is
sure whether the IMF's bitter medicine is the right prescription.
</P>
<P>
He predicted that if the baht's depreciation continues at its
current rate, the country will soon be thrust into an unmanageable
situation. "It will ruin most businesses in Thailand, unemployment
will reach unprecedented levels, and it could change society
overnight."
</P>
<P>
He is confident that the Thai economy will return healthy, but
said, "it is an international problem now."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
