<DOCNO> XIE19980109.0258 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. State Considers Limiting Toxin Chemicals in Fertilizer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, January 8 (Xinhua) -- While there is virtually no
regulation of fertilizer in the United States, Washington state
may soon be the first state to limit toxin chemicals.
</P>
<P>
The governor of Washington, Gary Locke, has proposed limiting
levels of lead, arsenic, cadmium and six other heavy metals and
requiring they be listed on fertilizer ingredient labels, local
reports said.
</P>
<P>
Locke's proposal, based on Canada's standards, is believed far
more comprehensive than other states that are considering new
rules or laws.
</P>
<P>
No research has proven consuming crops grown with
industrial-waste fertilizers are dangerous or safe to human
health. But a recent analysis of fertilizers made of industrial
waste revealed a high level of dioxin, a colorless and odorless
compound produced in the process such as waste incineration, steel
production, pulp and paper manufacturing and oil refining.
</P>
<P>
Dioxin is a prime suspect in cancers and reproductive
problems. The U.S. Environmental Protection Agency has said that
dioxin pollution is a threat to the general public.
</P>
<P>
Locke's bill would increase fertilizer testing, boost penalties
for violations and set aside money for a three-year study of the
pathway of heavy metals from factories to fertilizers to food.
</P>
<P>
It would also require a label on all commercial fertilizers
showing the list of the nine heavy metals and a statement that the
product meets the standards. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980109.0259 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
