<HEADLINE> Croatian President Stresses Cooperation with U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Croatia seeks to develop a
partnership and closer economic cooperation with the United
States, said Croatia's President Franjo Tudjman, during the
reception of William Montgomery, the new U.S. ambassador to
Croatia, at the presidential palace Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The president also stressed that Croatia puts great importance
on developing "very friendly" relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Croatia is very interested in establishing a mutually
beneficial cooperative partnership between the two countries, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Tudjman expressed satisfaction over military cooperation
between Croatia and the U.S., and said it is now time to boost our
economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Croatia should also work to improve democracy and economy at
home and to take part in world affairs after the transitional
period of establishing independence and democracy, Tudjman said.
</P>
<P>
The new U.S. ambassador stressed the need for Croatia to play a
role in ensuring a stable peace in the region.
</P>
<P>
Croatia is critical to the implementation of the 1995 Dayton
agreement and the establishment of long-term peace and stability
in the region, Montgomery said.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador expressed the hope that the two countries would
become active partners. He said the U.S. would back Croatia in its
efforts to play a more active part in Europe and NATO.
</P>
<P>
Before Croatia can fully participate in the process of
integrating with Europe, he said, it should give up its autocratic
rule and ensure full democracy. It should also work to establish a
competitive world market economy.
</P>
<P>
Croatia should also fully implement the Dayton Peace Accords
and the 1995 Erdut Peace Accords under which Eastern Slavonia, the
last Serb-held part of Croatia, is to be reintegrated with Croatia
this January, he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. ambassador said he wants to see national
reconciliation and good relationships with neighboring countries
achieved in Croatia.
</P>
<P>
Montgomery once served as ambassador to Bulgaria. He was a
presidential advisor on the implementation of the Dayton Peace
Accords before his recent appointment. 
</P>
