<HEADLINE> Political Pact Passed for Combating Crimes in Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Five Albanian parties in the
ruling coalition signed a political pact Thursday that empowers
the country's law enforcement agencies to combat organized crime.
</P>
<P>
The pact, signed by the Socialist Party of Albania, the Social
Democratic Party, the Union for Human Rights Party, the Agrarian
Party and the Democratic Alliance Party, also calls for the
surrender of arms by the public and the establishment of a
permanent anti-Mafia committee in parliament.
</P>
<P>
The pact, the most severe warning issued by the new coalition
government since its establishment last July, threatens to charge
persons who disseminate anti-constitution and -stability
statements that incite crime or terrorism that results in crime.
</P>
<P>
The five parties called on all Albanians to take part in the
fight against organized crime and terrorist activities and urged
President Rexhep Meidani to openly support the struggle.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman for Albanian Prime Minister Fatos Nano said
Thursday that the Nano government supports the political pact
signed by the five parties and will take all necessary steps to
strengthen the struggle against crime.
</P>
<P>
Organized crimes and terrorist attacks have become more rampant
in Albania in recent weeks. Ten people including four policemen
were killed and several policemen and civilians injured in the
first week of 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
