<HEADLINE> Turkey, European Countries to Curb Kurdish Immigrants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Turkey and seven European Union
countries agreed Thursday to strengthen efforts to curb the inflow
of Kurdish immigrants via Italy's poorly checked borders and
intensify their fights against organized crime.
</P>
<P>
Police chiefs and security officials from Italy, Turkey,
Germany, France, the Netherlands, Austria, Belgium and Greece came
up with the measures with a day-long meeting in Rome in response
to the recent influx of more than 1,200 Kurds into Italy.
</P>
<P>
A statement released by Italy's Interior Ministry after the
talks said the officials "defined common actions plans" with
respect to tightening the controls of immigrants at borders and
conducting incisive investigations into organized crime,
particularly with regard to trafficking suspects.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was called by Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi
after several European Union countries voiced their concern about
illegal immigrants entering the Schengen border-free area of
Europe via Italy.
</P>
<P>
Turkey refused to sign an eight-point declaration of intent
drawn by the police chiefs, but promised to continue to cooperate
in the fight against organized crime in illegal immigration.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in Florence Thursday morning, Italian Foreign Minister
Lamberto Dini said the Italian diplomatic pressure on Turkey to
stem the flow of immigrants from its shores was starting to bear
fruit.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, police in the southern Italian region of Calabria
reported that 416 of the over 800 refugees arriving there from
Turkey on December 27 had applied for political asylum.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has criticized Italy's willingness to offer political
asylum to Kurds, saying it will only encourage more to follow. It
also claims that Kurds are economic, rather than political
refugees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
