<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Tax Revenue Keeps Growing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 9 (Xinhua) -- China's industrial and
commercial tax revenue kept its vigorous rising momentum in 1997,
with its growth rate outstripping the increase of the national GDP.
</P>
<P>
The country collected 754.8 billion yuan (90.0 billion US
dollars) in industrial and commercial taxes last year, up 17.2
percent from the previous year, compared with the 8.8 percent GDP
growth last year, according to a report released by the State
Administration of Taxation.
</P>
<P>
This rise was the largest ever, and last year was the fifth
consecutive year that China's industrial and commercial tax
revenue recorded eye-catching growth, said Xiang Huaicheng, deputy
director of the State Administration of Taxation.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the tax reform and its continuing improvement,
China's taxation has made much progress with the tax revenues of
both the central and local governments growing rapidly.
</P>
<P>
Taxes collected for the central government grew 19.3 percent to
426.1 billion yuan in 1997. That part of the tax levy accounted
for 56.5 percent of the overall industrial and commercial tax
revenue, rising 0.9 of a percentage point from the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The local governments' tax collection last year amounted to
328.7 billion yuan, an increase of 14.6 percent from 1996.
</P>
<P>
To support the reforms and opening-up policy as well as
economic growth, China will reinforce the taxation management this
year and try to promote the tax collection in tandem with the GDP
growth.
</P>
<P>
China has set its 1998 industrial and commercial tax revenue
target at about 832.5 billion yuan, up 11 percent over 1997's
figure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
