<HEADLINE> Thai Diplomats Told to Slash Housing Costs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 9 (Xinhua) -- The Thai Foreign Ministry has
asked Thai diplomats overseas to trim housing budgets by 30
percent or find the cash themselves.
</P>
<P>
The ministry's Permanent Secretary Saroj Chavanaviraj quoted
Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai as saying that the government could
not afford what was being spent due to economy slowdown, local
press reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The ministry has 619 diplomats overseas.
</P>
<P>
In a telegram recently circulated to Thai embassies, Saroj made
it clear that the plea for savings applied across the board.
</P>
<P>
It included spending on water, electricity, and other basic
expenses.
</P>
<P>
According to Saroj, the Thai Foreign Ministry was the worst
affected by the flotation of the baht in July, effectively losing
1,200 million baht from its 1998 budget.
</P>
<P>
The ministry might this year recall 84 diplomats whose terms
are due to end in 1999 if the economy does not improve, a source
at the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The ministry has already decided not to replace 73 diplomats
whose terms expire this year.  
</P>
