<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka to Set Up 2 Fishing Harbors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka is to set up two
fishing harbors at a cost of 263 million Rupees (4.38 million U.S.
dollars) in the coming years, a senior government official said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Fisheries and Aquatic Resources Minister Mahinda Rajapakse said
the harbor at Hikkaduwa in the deep south will be completed in two
years at a cost of 72 million Rupees (1.2 million dollars) while
another one at Moratuwa-Panadura near Colombo will be completed in
one and a half years with an investment of 191 million Rupees
(3.18 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The projects are expected to boost fish production, increase
fishermen's earnings and strengthen the institutions that support
and provide service to the fishery industry.
</P>
<P>
The minister said feasibility studies are being conducted to
determine locations for more harbors.
</P>
<P>
He said in addition to the construction of harbors, attention
will also be given to the development of infrastructure, such as
electricity, drinking water, roads and health and education
facilities, in the fishing villages and coastal areas.  
</P>
