<DOCNO> XIE19980109.0268 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panic Buying Hits Jakarta, Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 9 (Xinhua) -- Panic buying hit stores across
Indonesia's capital city of Jakarta Thursday after a dramatic fall
in the value of the national currency and many people were worried
about a possible price hike in the near future.
</P>
<P>
Long queues were seen at most supermarkets with basic
foodstuffs such as rice and instant noodles vanishing from
shelves.
</P>
<P>
"Poorer people were digging into their pockets to buy half a
dozen tins of sardines," local press Friday quoted one shopper who
joined the rush as saying.
</P>
<P>
"Some people were buying ridiculous things like bottle water,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
"Cars were backed up to the main road and beyond for around 500
meters as people tried to get near the stores," said one shopper.
</P>
<P>
Reports from provinces said similar rushes were experienced in
many parts of the country. Basics such as rice, sugar and cooking
oil disappeared off supermarket shelves.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's economy has been spiraling downward since July last
year, with consumer prices and unemployment rising steadily.
</P>
<P>
But the public reaction to Thursday's free fall by the
Indonesian rupiah was the first sign that people were seriously
worried.
</P>
<P>
Rupiah tumbled in value by more than 22 percent Thursday,
hitting a record low of 11,000 to the US dollar at the end of the
day's trading. The rupiah has lost about 300 percent of its value
against the greenback since last July.
</P>
<P>
Head of National Logistics Agency (Bulog) Beddu Amang issued a
statement last night that there was no need for concern since
stocks were adequate and that there would be no price rises.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, military authorities called for calm as some shops
closed after selling out.
</P>
<P>
In an attempt to prevent riots and looting, the City Police
dispatched thousands of officers, including undercover personnel,
to safeguard supermarkets and retail stores.
</P>
<P>
According to City Police Chief Maj. Gen. Hamami Nata, the city
was safe. He said all rumors of riots and chaos were untrue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
