<HEADLINE> Anand Wins Sixth Game FIDE Chess Championship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVE, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Indian challenger Viswanathan
Anand upset defending champion Anatoly Karpov of Russia in the
sixth game of the FIDE World Chess Championship in Lausanne,
Switzerland, on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The 28-year-old Anand won the sixth game of the finals in four
hours to equal the points with 3-3, and therefore forced a
tiebreaker.
</P>
<P>
With the advantage of playing white, Anand forced Karpov to
resigned at the 42nd moves.
</P>
<P>
They have to compete in a decisive game later this week to
decide the winner. The winner of the competition gets a 1.4
million U.S. dollars prize money and the runner-up has 768,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
