<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia to Maintain Macro-Economy Stability </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslavia must retain the
stability of its macro-economy and carry out economic reforms, the
Yugoslav news agency Tanjug quoted Deputy Prime Minister Danko
Djunich as saying.
</P>
<P>
Djunich made the remark at a workshop on 1998 economic policy
held Thursday. He said the country must keep its macro-economy
stable in order to realize speedy economic growth, to increase
employment and raise the living standard.
</P>
<P>
He also said it was not enough for the country to just continue
to take the same measures on monetary and financial policy as it
did in the past to sustain the economy. The country must take
decisive steps toward reform to sustain macro-economic stability,
he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Djunich said Yugoslavia must realize economic integration with
Europe and the world. He added that it must do its best to
continue to receive the most-favored-nation treatment it receives
from the European Commission. For that reason, the country's large
enterprises must seek foreign partners as soon as possible, he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
