<HEADLINE> Yugoslav Federal Court Rejects Montenegro Court Decisions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The Yugoslav Federal Court
turned down another 29 decisions by the Montenegro Republic
Constitutional Court Thursday over the disputes that occurred
during presidential elections in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Head of the Yugoslav Federal Court Borivoje Vukichevic told the
press that the Montenegrin court has to review their decisions
again and remove the names of disqualified voters from the
eligibility list, the Yugoslav news agency Tanjug reported.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Court rejected some of the Montenegrin court's
decisions Tuesday. The Montenegrin court has been accused of
illegal activities regarding decisions over voter's qualifications
before the Yugoslav Republic's presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
However, incumbent Prime Minister Milo Djukanovic, who won the
second round of elections with a marginal majority last October,
opposed the Federal Court's rejection, accusing the court of
misusing its power, a local report said.
</P>
<P>
Djukanovic said the decisions of the Federal Court, which
wanted to influence the situation of the Montenegro Republic after
its presidential elections, were not legally binding, the report
added.
</P>
<P>
President of the Montenegro Republic Momir Bulatovic brought a
lawsuit against the Constitutional Court of Montenegro last
November after the court rejected his allegations that malpractice
existed in the second round of presidential elections last
October. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980109.0285 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Social Insurance Regulations for South China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, January 9 (Xinhua) -- The People's Congress of the
Shantou Special Economic Zone (SEZ) in China's Guangdong
Province recently approved its first regional regulations on social
insurance for employees.
</P>
<P>
The regulations, which is scheduled to take effect March 1, say
that enterprises within the SEZ are required to have a social
insurance system and all employees should buy insurance policies
that are geared to their respective incomes.
</P>
<P>
Pensions and medical insurance costs are jointly covered by
employees, the enterprises where they work, and the state, the
regulations say.
</P>
<P>
The cost of insurance covering child-bearing, unemployment, and
injuries on the job is covered by the state and the enterprises in
agreed-upon amounts.
</P>
<P>
The SEZ has set up an organization to supervise revenues,
expenditures, and the operation of social insurance funds to stop
any institution or individual from misappropriating public funds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980109.0286 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil Records Motor Vehicle Output in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The Brazilian motor vehicle
industry output reached an unprecedented figure of 2.077 million
units last year, the Brazilian Association of Motor Vehicle
Manufacturers said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
This figure represents a 14.5 percent growth over the 1.804
million units in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Of the total number of units, 1.86 million, or 89.5 percent,
were reserved for the domestic market, while the rest were
exported. Domestic sales grew 11 percent over the 1.067 million
of the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Brazilian automobile output suffered a drastic drop in the last
two months of 1997. November output dropped 32 percent and 21
percent in december, compared to the previous months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
