<HEADLINE> Over 60 Tons of Drugs Seized in Mexico </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The Mexican Federal Roads
Police (PFC) confiscated a total of 59,964.313 kilograms of
marijuana and 4,770.796 kilograms of cocaine during 1997, a
communique revealed here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The PFC bulletin said that the seizures made last year are a
record compared to the last seven years, and a 32.7 percent
increase compared to 1996.
</P>
<P>
The number of captures of alleged drug traffickers increased
30.9 percent during 1997, with 355 persons, against 271 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The roads police also said that during its inspection and
vigilance tasks of 48,000 kilometers of federal roads, and with
the implementation of special programs on the matter, 2,911
alleged criminals were detained last year.
</P>
<P>
Car theft was the cause of most of the captures, numbering
1,397. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
