<DOCNO> XIE19980109.0294 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gebrselassie, Jones, Kipketer up for Owens Award </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Wilson Kipketer of Denmark,
800 meters runner, Ethiopian distance runner Haile Gebrselassie
and American sprinter Marion Jones were named Thursday as
finalists for the Jesse Owens International Trophy Award.
</P>
<P>
The winner of the 18th annual award will be voted by a
worldwide panel later this month. Michael Johnson won the award in
1996 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
Kipketer equalled and then twice broke the 800 meters record of
1:41.73 set by Sebastian Coe in 1981. That was the oldest world
record in track and field. The native Kenyan matched Coe in
Stockholm, clocked 1:41.24 in Zurich and 10 days later ran 1:41.11
in Cologne.
</P>
<P>
Gebrselassie, the world champion at 10,000 meters for the third
consecutive time, set world records for the 10,000 in Oslo in July
and for the 5,000 in Zurich in August (both marks since broken).
</P>
<P>
Jones, the women's world champion at 100 meters, recorded
the fastest times in the world last year over both 100 and 200
meters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
