<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Warns Paris Over Blocking Waste Shipments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU)'s
executive body, the European Commission, today accused France of
violating EU laws by blocking imports of plastic waste from
Germany.
</P>
<P>
The Commission said in a statement that it would seek legal
proceedings against Paris unless it stopped blocking shipments of
plastic waste from Germany.
</P>
<P>
Under an EU regulation passed in 1993, EU member countries are
not allowed to block waste shipments from other members if they
are on the so-called green list of relatively harmless waste,
including solid plastic.
</P>
<P>
The EU executive noted that the reasons for this move made by
Paris were more political than practical since the French
government could not justify convincingly the move.
</P>
<P>
The commission was also sending France a warning letter telling
it about its failure to comply with an EU law obliging it to
provide Brussels with data on ozone levels. Paris is four years
over the deadline.
</P>
<P>
It said in a statement that by doing so, the Commission showed
the importance it attached to the EU's air quality directive.
</P>
<P>
However, the Commission said that it was ending legal
proceedings against France for failing to give special protection
to the Loire estuary, a key area for many wild birds.
</P>
<P>
Paris promised to take action to protect the area, meaning that
projects for new infrastructure there would be assessed for their
environmental impact. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980109.0302 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton May Travel to Africa in March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 8 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton might
travel to Africa as early as March, which would be the beginning
of a series of foreign trips this year, U.S. officials said today.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's advisers would be looking at a range of possible
dates for the African travel and one of them was March, but no
decision had been made, they said.
</P>
<P>
The United States has paid more attention to the continent
since the end of the Cold War. Two secretaries of state -- Warren
Christopher in 1996 and Madeleine Albright in 1997 -- have
traveled there, trying to make closer ties between the United
States and African nations.
</P>
<P>
Clinton originally planned to start his schedule of foreign
travel in February by visiting India and Pakistan, but was forced
to postpone because of political turmoil in the two countries.
Advisers are now looking at next fall for that trip, which might
include a stop in Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
In April Clinton will go to Chile for a Latin America summit
and in May he will take a trip to Britain for a summit of the
seven industrial countries plus Russia.
</P>
<P>
A trip to Russia is also not ruled out once Russia's Duma
approves an arms reduction treaty.
</P>
<P>
Clinton is also expected to pay an official visit to China as
well.
</P>
<P>
In November he will go to Malaysia to attend the annual APEC
summit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980109.0303 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Bikers to Launch Campaign Against EU Plans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, January 8 (Xinhua) -- A European bikers' rights
organization said today that its bikers were planning to launch a
campaign Saturday to fight European Union (EU) plans to make the
scrapping of used vehicles more environmentally friendly.
</P>
<P>
The Federation of European Motorcyclists (FEMA), which has a
total of 400,000 members, said that the campaign would be aimed at
getting motorbikes excluded from the EU's green scrapping plans.
</P>
<P>
The plans, which were proposed last July by the EU executive,
the European Commission, will oblige the automobile industry to
re-use or recycle 10 percent more of material from scrapped
vehicles by the year 2005 if adopted. The percentage now is 75.
</P>
<P>
Under the plans, a total of 95 percent of the metal, plastic,
glass and other materials used in vehicles will have to be re-used
or recycled by the year of 2015.
</P>
<P>
Manufacturers will be obliged to change the design of vehicles
to make the raw materials easier to recover, while final users
will have to obtain a "certificate of destruction" from a
registered dismantler to show that they have disposed of their
vehicle properly.
</P>
<P>
Though most parts of the directive will mainly concern cars,
FEMA said the so-called "certificate of destruction" would likely
end the old practice of rebuilding bikes from used parts. FEMA
called the practice "widespread and environmentally friendly."
</P>
<P>
FEMA explains that motorbikes are different from cars and
should not be treated as the same, adding that motorbikes, unlike
cars, don't reach the end of their life and its parts have to be
sold to other people for rebuilding their bikes or sold as scrap.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980109.0304 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Okays 670 Mln Dlr Payment to Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund (IMF) today approved the sixth quarterly review of the
economic development and agreed to release an about 670 million
U.S. dollar loan under the Extended Fund Facility for Russia.
</P>
<P>
An IMF press statement noted that Russia's economic growth has
resumed, inflation has remained on a downward trend, and
structural reforms have gained renewed momentum. However, there is
some concern about progress in addressing the fiscal problem, in
particular low revenue collection.
</P>
<P>
The IMF welcomes the Russian government's action plan to
address the fiscal situation, which included measures to improve
tax collection, as well as to strengthen expenditure control and
define realistic spending policies. "Full implementation of this
plan will be crucial," the IMF stressed.
</P>
<P>
The institution also welcomes the fact that, following initial
delays in responding to capital outflows in the fall of 1997, the
Central Bank of Russia's tightening of monetary policy in December
helped to stabilize financial market conditions.
</P>
<P>
Confronting growing criticism of the harsh demands it has
proposed to rescue economies in Asia, the IMF is also prepared for
the next disbursement of 2 billion dollars to South Korea. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980109.0305 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Supports Sending Mission to Algeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) has
expressed its support for plans to send a mission to Algeria but
has not decided on the timing, mandate or level of the
fact-finding team, it was learned here today.
</P>
<P>
Sources said the Algerian government had not been contacted yet
and therefore it was too early to say whether the North African
country would approve such a mission or not.
</P>
<P>
The Algerian government has so far rejected all foreign bids
for investigation or mediation with the Muslim rebels on whom the
recent massacres are mainly blamed, saying that they were
unacceptable interference.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that the proposed mission had been discussed
by the 15 EU member countries in Brussels and would be taken up by
the European Council's political committee on January 13.
</P>
<P>
But the sources added that the EU had not decided yet on the
timing, mandate or level of the mission.
</P>
<P>
The mission would be possibly composed by representatives from
Britain, the current EU presidency country, Luxembourg, the
previous president, and Austria, which will take over the
presidency role in the second half of this year.
</P>
<P>
More than 65,000 people have been killed in Algeria's
six-year-old civil war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
