<HEADLINE> Stocks Plunge on Wall Street </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Stocks fell sharply in New York
today, with another rocky day on Asian markets and another
discouraging profit forecast from the technology group.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average plunged 99.65 points to
7,802.62.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 5-to-3 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume was extremely heavy
again, totaling 651 million shares at the closing, the second
straight session above 650 million and the fourth straight above
600 million.
</P>
<P>
Broad-market indicators also suffered sizable losses, although
the technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index market only fell
modestly.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list fell 7.96 to 956.04, and
the NYSE composite index fell 4.54 to 501.64.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index fell 6.15 to 1,555.55, and the
American Stock Exchange composite index fell 6.73 to 667.56.
</P>
<P>
The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 4.08 to
425.71.
</P>
<P>
Investors felt uneasy about the uncertain economic growth in
Southeast Asia. The Indonesian currency lost more than one-fourth
of its value and the stock market dropped 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's woes dragged down other Southeast Asian markets,
with Hong Kong stocks sliding another 3 percent on top of
Wednesday' 6 percent dive; Singapore shares and Philippine shares
sinking again.
</P>
<P>
The market was not affected much by two tame inflation
related data in the U.S..  
</P>
</TEXT>
