<HEADLINE> Cohen's Asia Trip to Stress Engagement in Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 8 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Defense Secretary
William Cohen will send a message to Asian countries during his
visit that the United States will remain engaged in the region
"now and in the future," a senior U.S. defense official said at a
Pentagon press conference.
</P>
<P>
"We have profound, deep and abiding interests in Southeast
Asia," the official told reporters ahead of a January 12-22 visit
to China and six other Asian countries by Defense Secretary Cohen.
</P>
<P>
The official, asked not to be identified, said there was a
sense of vulnerability, of uncertainty in Asia because of the
recent economic crisis, and those stricken by the crisis were
hoping that the United States would be involved in helping resolve
the crisis. "That's what this trip is about," he said.
</P>
<P>
Cohen would emphasize the strategic and economic importance of
both Northeast and Southeast Asia during his visit to Malaysia,
Indonesia, Singapore, Thailand, China, Japan and South Korea, the
official said.
</P>
<P>
"We are trying to work closely in all avenues of our government
-- the Department of the Treasury, the White House, State and
Defense (Departments) -- on our relationship with Southeast Asian
countries and try to convey to them our commitment to stand with
them during this tie of uncertainly," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
