<HEADLINE> 2 Key US Senators Back Longer Stay of GIs in Bosnia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Two key U.S. Democratic
senators back from Bosnia said today they support a continued U.S.
military presence in the region and called on Europe to bear the
peacekeeping burden for years to come.
</P>
<P>
"An outside force is going to be needed for a long period of
time, perhaps a decade or more, but we just cannot stay that
long," said Sen. Carl Levin, D-Mich., ranking Democrat on the
Senate Armed Services Committee.
</P>
<P>
Levin and Sen. Jack Reed, D-R.I., predicted that Congress would
stop short of cutting off funding for the Bosnia deployment, but
would insist that President Bill Clinton inform allies that U.S.
troops will not be in Bosnia indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
Levin and Reed returned today from a four-day trip to Bosnia,
where they met with top U.S. and allied commanders as well as
local officials
</P>
<P>
Last month, Clinton announced that it is a mistake to set a
deadline for the withdrawal of U.S. troops from Bosnia and decided
that the U.S. will continue to deploy troops in the country beyond
June this year.
</P>
<P>
The Republican-controlled Congress last year decided to cut off
funding for the U.S. troops deployed in Bosnia after the deadline
and any further funding would require Clinton to explain why to
Congress.
</P>
<P>
The administration's new stance is expected to spark a major
foreign policy debate on Capitol Hill in the coming months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
