<HEADLINE> US Senate Spends 60 Mln Dlrs Yearly on Investigations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The cost of the U.S. Senate
investigations over alleged abuses has averaged more than 60
million dollars a year since Republicans took control of the
chamber in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The secretary of the Senate reported that the cost of
investigations reached 188.7 million dollars through September 30,
1997.
</P>
<P>
The money goes for committee hearings to scrutinize
presidential nominees and examine the performance of federal
agencies, fulfilling the chamber's watchdog role assigned by the
Constitution.
</P>
<P>
It also has been spent since 1995 on high-profile
investigations of Clinton administration controversies, most
notably on Whitewater hearings and recently concluded campaign
finance hearings.
</P>
<P>
Senate Democrats allege the Republicans spent the money on
partisan attacks rather than legitimate examinations.
</P>
<P>
Republican National Committee spokesman Mike Collins retorted
that Clinton administration and Democratic Party officials have
nobody to blame but themselves. 
</P>
</TEXT>
