<DOCNO> XIE19980109.0310 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State Department Reaffirms U.S. Long-standing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. State Department on
Thursday welcomed the latest conciliatory remarks by the Iranian
president on cultural exchanges, but again reaffirmed U.S.
long-standing policy toward Iran for any improvement of ties.
</P>
<P>
"We welcome the continuation of a new tone in Iranian
statements. President (Mohammad) Khatami's extensive comments with
respect to U.S. civilization and values were interesting," State
Department James Rubin told reporters. "We also noted the
president's comments that the conduct or relations between nations
must be based on mutual respect and dignity."
</P>
<P>
President Khatami told CNN in an interview, broadcast on
Wednesday, that "nothing should prevent dialogue and understanding
between two nations, especially between their scholars and
thinkers."
</P>
<P>
"Right now, I recommend the exchange of professors, scholars,
writers, artists, journalists and tourists," the Iranian president
proposed.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said the United States would look closely and take a
serious look at what President Khatami had said "regarding
people-to-people exchanges and the people-to-people dialogue."
</P>
<P>
But he again stressed the importance of direct talks between
the two governments as the best way to address differences.
</P>
<P>
"We believe the best way to address our bilateral differences
would be to engage in a government-to-government dialogue," he
said. "we should sit down and air differences. We would raise our
concerns; the Iranians would raise their concerns."
</P>
<P>
With regard to any improvement of relations between the two
countries, Rubin said three issues must be tackled before
considering to take steps for political ties, which severed
following the Islamic revolution in 1979.
</P>
<P>
"Let me stress that changes in Iranian policies on support for
terror, the development of weapons of mass destruction, and
support for violent opposition to the Middle East peace process
remain key to forging a better relationship," he said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, White House spokesman Mike McCurry said President Bill
Clinton's foreign policy advisers will examine U.S. policy on
restricting cultural exchanges with Iran in light of positive
remarks by President Khatami.
</P>
<P>
"In the aftermath of President Khatami's interview last night,
that will be examined by the president foreign policy advisers,"
he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether it is possible to lift visa restrictions for the
exchanges of scholars and artists, McCurry said it would take time
for the president's advisers to make any decisions.
</P>
<P>
"It's way too soon to speculate on what, if any action, may
result," he said.
</P>
<P>
McCurry welcomed Khatami's remarks, describing them as
"positive remarks about the United States."
</P>
<P>
"The president (Bill Clinton) appreciates those positive
remarks. We welcome the fact that he wants a dialogue with the
American people and between two great civilization. That can be
useful," he said.
</P>
<P>
McCurry also stressed the importance of direct contacts between
U.S. and Iranian governments.
</P>
<P>
"It's also important to stress that the best way for issues to
be addressed is for governments to talk directly,"
</P>
<P>
He again made clear that the United States would only look at
deeds not words.
</P>
<P>
"Ultimately improvement in relations depend upon not just what
Iran says but what Iran does," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
