<HEADLINE> Storms Lead to Heavy Damages in Central, East U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Stroms in central and east
United States in the last couple of days brought heavy damages to
houses and roads, leading to six deaths, evacuations and more than
a million people without electricity.
</P>
<P>
The emergency spillway on a small dam in Quitman, Mississippi,
failed this morning, sending a gush of floodwaters downstream and
prompting evacuations of low-lying areas in the communities of
Desoto and Shubuta, reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
In North Carolina, heavy rains across the western part of the
state forced many residents to evacuate from their homes.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, a 5-year-old girl was washed away and killed by
floodwater in south of Birmingham, Alabama, and a 62-year-old
woman in Owingsville, Kentucky, drowned when she fell off a foot
bridge into a rain-swollen creek.
</P>
<P>
In Carter County, Tennessee, four people were confirmed dead
today in flooding. A police helicopter rescued 18 people from a
rooftop in the county.
</P>
<P>
The rain was companied with high wind, fog and ice. In Easley,
South Carolina, four people were treated at hospitals late
Wednesday after a tornado-strong storm destroyed several mobile
homes. In Camden of the state, storms knocked down trees and power
lines.
</P>
<P>
The rainfall in the Northeast turned to ice in many areas. By
Thursday afternoon, 185,000 customers or 35 percent of Central
Maine Power's business, were without electricity after icy buildup
and wind knocked tree limbs onto power lines.
</P>
<P>
In addition, 100,000 customers lost power in upstate New York,
20,000 in New Hampshire and 10,000 in Vermont.
</P>
<P>
The storms came in an unseasonal warm weather in the central
and east regions. The warm whether this week drives people to put
off sweaters. In some areas that usually should be frozen at this
time, grass began to grow up. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
