<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Drug, Alcohol Abuse Contribute to Prison </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Eighty percent of the adults
in U.S. prisons are locked up because of criminal activities
linked to drug and alcohol abuse, said a report from a group
urging increased spending on prison drug treatment programs.
</P>
<P>
The report by the National Center on Addiction and Substance
Abuse urged governments, particularly the states, to spend more
money to help 1.4 million inmates quit their habits before
returning to society.
</P>
<P>
The report said these prisoners also need job training, health
care and religious instruction.
</P>
<P>
"The most troublesome aspect of these grim statistics is that
the country is doing so little about them," James Califano,
president of the Columbia University-based center, told a news
conference.
</P>
<P>
At the same gathering, Barry McCaffrey, director of the White
House Office of National Drug Control Policy, said the government
has begun to spend more on treatment as it focused its efforts on
keeping the nation's teens and children from turning to drugs.
</P>
<P>
But McCaffrey said the federal government alone can't be the
solution.
</P>
<P>
The 281-page drugs report said the tripling of America's prison
population, from 500,000 in 1980 to 1.7 million in 1996, was due
mainly to criminal acts influenced by drugs and/or alcohol.
</P>
<P>
Most of the inmates, more than 1 million, are housed in state
prisons.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1.7 million total, 1.4 million adult men and women were
incarcerated for behavior influenced by alcohol or narcotics.
Among the 1.4 million are parents of more than 2 million children,
the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
